1	all these the parthian now some ages past
1	by great arsaces led who founded first
1	that empire under his dominion holds 
1	from the luxurious kings of antioch won 
1	and just in time thou com st to have a view
1	of his great power for now the parthian king
1	in ctesiphon hath gathered all his host
1	against the scythian whose incursions wild
1	have wasted sogdiana to her aid
1	he marches now in haste see though from far 
1	his thousands in what martial equipage
1	they issue forth steel bows and shafts their arms 
1	of equal dread in flight or in pursuit 
1	all horsemen in which fight they most excel 
1	see how in warlike muster they appear 
1	in rhombs and wedges and half moons and wings 
1	he looked and saw what numbers numberless
1	the city gates outpoured light armed troops
1	in coats of mail and military pride 
1	in mail their horses clad yet fleet and strong 
1	prauncing their riders bore the flower and choice
1	of many provinces from bound to bound 
1	from arachosia from candaor east 
1	and margiana to the hyrcanian cliffs
1	of caucasus and dark iberian dales 
1	from atropatia and the neighbouring plains
1	of adiabene media and the south
1	of susiana to balsara s haven 
1	he saw them in their forms of battle ranged 
1	how quick they wheeled and flying behind them shot
1	sharp sleet of arrowy showers against the face
1	of their pursuers and overcame by flight 
1	the field all iron cast a gleaming brown 
1	nor wanted clouds of foot nor on each horn 
1	cuirassiers all in steel for standing fight 
1	chariots or elephants indorsed with towers
1	of archers nor of labouring pioners
1	to lay hills plain fell woods or valleys fill 
1	or where plain was raise hill or overlay
1	with bridges rivers proud as with a yoke 
1	mules after these camels and dromedaries 
1	and waggons fraught with utensils of war 
1	such forces met not nor so wide a camp 
1	when agrican with all his northern powers 
1	besieged albracea as romances tell 
1	the city of gallaphrone from thence to win
1	the fairest of her sex angelica 
1	his daughter sought by many prowest knights 
1	both paynim and the peers of charlemane 
1	such and so numerous was their chivalry 
1	at sight whereof the fiend yet more presumed 
1	and to our saviour thus his words renewed 
1	 that thou may st know i seek not to engage
1	thy virtue and not every way secure
1	on no slight grounds thy safety hear and mark
1	to what end i have brought thee hither and shew
1	all this fair sight thy kingdom though foretold
1	by prophet or by angel unless thou
1	endeavour as thy father david did 
1	thou never shalt obtain prediction still
1	in all things and all men supposes means 
1	without means used what it predicts revokes 
1	but say thou wert possessed of david s throne
1	by free consent of all none opposite 
1	long to enjoy it quiet and secure
1	between two such enclosing enemies 
1	roman and parthian therefore one of these
1	thou must make sure thy own the parthian first 
1	by my advice as nearer and of late
1	found able by invasion to annoy
1	thy country and captive lead away her kings 
1	antigonus and old hyrcanus bound 
1	maugre the roman it shall be my task
1	to render thee the parthian at dispose 
1	choose which thou wilt by conquest or by league 
1	by him thou shalt regain without him not 
1	that which alone can truly reinstall thee
1	in david s royal seat his true successor 
1	deliverance of thy brethren those ten tribes
1	whose offspring in his territory yet serve
1	in habor and among the medes dispersed 
1	the sons of jacob two of joseph lost
1	thus long from israel serving as of old
1	this offer sets before thee to deliver 
1	these if from servitude thou shalt restore
1	to their inheritance then nor till then 
1	thou on the throne of david in full glory 
1	shalt reign and rome or caesar not need fear 
1	to whom our saviour answered thus unmoved 
1	 much ostentation vain of fleshly arm
1	and fragile arms much instrument of war 
1	long in preparing soon to nothing brought 
1	before mine eyes thou hast set and in my ear
1	vented much policy and projects deep
1	of enemies of aids battles and leagues 
1	plausible to the world to me worth naught 
1	means i must use thou say st prediction else
1	will unpredict and fail me of the throne 
1	my time i told thee and that time for thee
1	were better farthest off is not yet come 
1	when that comes think not thou to find me slack
1	on my part aught endeavouring or to need
1	thy politic maxims or that cumbersome
1	luggage of war there shewn me argument
1	of human weakness rather than of strength 
1	my brethren as thou call st them those ten tribes 
1	i must deliver if i mean to reign
1	david s true heir and his full sceptre sway
1	to just extent over all israel s sons 
1	but whence to thee this zeal where was it then
1	for israel or for david or his throne 
1	when thou stood st up his tempter to the pride
1	of numbering israel which cost the lives
1	of threescore and ten thousand israelites
1	by three days pestilence such was thy zeal
1	to israel then the same that now to me 
1	as for those captive tribes themselves were they
1	who wrought their own captivity fell off
1	from god to worship calves the deities
1	and all the idolatries of heathen round 
1	besides their other worse than heathenish crimes 
1	nor in the land of their captivity
1	humbled themselves or penitent besought
1	the god of their forefathers but so died
1	impenitent and left a race behind
1	like to themselves distinguishable scarce
1	from gentiles but by circumcision vain 
1	and god with idols in their worship joined 
1	should i of these the liberty regard 
1	who freed as to their ancient patrimony 
1	unhumbled unrepentant unreformed 
1	headlong would follow and to their gods perhaps
1	of bethel and of dan no let them serve
1	their enemies who serve idols with god 
1	yet he at length time to himself best known 
1	remembering abraham by some wondrous call
1	may bring them back repentant and sincere 
1	and at their passing cleave the assyrian flood 
1	while to their native land with joy they haste 
1	as the red sea and jordan once he cleft 
1	when to the promised land their fathers passed 
1	to his due time and providence i leave them 
1	so spake israel s true king and to the fiend
1	made answer meet that made void all his wiles 
1	so fares it when with truth falsehood contends 
1	perplexed and troubled at his bad success
1	the tempter stood nor had what to reply 
1	discovered in his fraud thrown from his hope
1	so oft and the persuasive rhetoric
1	that sleeked his tongue and won so much on eve 
1	so little here nay lost but eve was eve 
1	this far his over match who self deceived
1	and rash beforehand had no better weighed
1	the strength he was to cope with or his own 
1	but as a man who had been matchless held
1	in cunning over reached where least he thought 
1	to salve his credit and for very spite 
1	still will be tempting him who foils him still 
1	and never cease though to his shame the more 
1	or as a swarm of flies in vintage time 
1	about the wine press where sweet must is poured 
1	beat off returns as oft with humming sound 
1	or surging waves against a solid rock 
1	though all to shivers dashed the assault renew 
1	 vain battery and in froth or bubbles end 
1	so satan whom repulse upon repulse
1	met ever and to shameful silence brought 
1	yet gives not o er though desperate of success 
1	and his vain importunity pursues 
1	he brought our saviour to the western side
1	of that high mountain whence he might behold
1	another plain long but in breadth not wide 
1	washed by the southern sea and on the north
1	to equal length backed with a ridge of hills
1	that screened the fruits of the earth and seats of men
1	from cold septentrion blasts thence in the midst
1	divided by a river off whose banks
1	on each side an imperial city stood 
1	with towers and temples proudly elevate
1	on seven small hills with palaces adorned 
1	porches and theatres baths aqueducts 
1	statues and trophies and triumphal arcs 
1	gardens and groves presented to his eyes
1	above the highth of mountains interposed 
1	by what strange parallax or optic skill
1	of vision multiplied through air or glass
1	of telescope were curious to enquire 
1	and now the tempter thus his silence broke 
1	 the city which thou seest no other deem
1	than great and glorious rome queen of the earth
1	so far renowned and with the spoils enriched
1	of nations there the capitol thou seest 
1	above the rest lifting his stately head
1	on the tarpeian rock her citadel
1	impregnable and there mount palatine 
1	the imperial palace compass huge and high
1	the structure skill of noblest architects 
1	with gilded battlements conspicuous far 
1	turrets and terraces and glittering spires 
1	many a fair edifice besides more like
1	houses of gods so well i have disposed
1	my aerie microscope thou may st behold 
1	outside and inside both pillars and roofs
1	carved work the hand of famed artificers
1	in cedar marble ivory or gold 
1	thence to the gates cast round thine eye and see
1	what conflux issuing forth or entering in 
1	praetors proconsuls to their provinces
1	hasting or on return in robes of state 
1	lictors and rods the ensigns of their power 
1	legions and cohorts turms of horse and wings 
1	or embassies from regions far remote 
1	in various habits on the appian road 
1	or on the aemilian some from farthest south 
1	syene and where the shadow both way falls 
1	meroe nilotic isle and more to west 
1	the realm of bocchus to the blackmoor sea 
1	from the asian kings and parthian among these 
1	and utmost indian isle taprobane 
1	dusk faces with white silken turbants wreathed 
1	from gallia gades and the british west 
1	germans and scythians and sarmatians north
1	beyond danubius to the tauric pool 
1	all nations now to rome obedience pay 
1	to rome s great emperor whose wide domain 
1	in ample territory wealth and power 
1	civility of manners arts and arms 
1	and long renown thou justly may st prefer
1	before the parthian these two thrones except 
1	the rest are barbarous and scarce worth the sight 
1	shared among petty kings too far removed 
1	these having shewn thee i have shewn thee all
1	the kingdoms of the world and all their glory 
1	this emperor hath no son and now is old 
1	old and lascivious and from rome retired
1	to capreae an island small but strong
1	on the campanian shore with purpose there
1	his horrid lusts in private to enjoy 
1	committing to a wicked favourite
1	all public cares and yet of him suspicious 
1	hated of all and hating with what ease 
1	endued with regal virtues as thou art 
1	appearing and beginning noble deeds 
1	might st thou expel this monster from his throne 
1	now made a sty and in his place ascending 
1	a victor people free from servile yoke 
1	and with my help thou may st to me the power
1	is given and by that right i give it thee 
1	aim therefore at no less than all the world 
1	aim at the highest without the highest attained 
1	will be for thee no sitting or not long 
1	on david s throne be prophesied what will 
1	to whom the son of god unmoved replied 
1	 nor doth this grandeur and majestic shew
1	of luxury though called magnificence 
1	more than of arms before allure mine eye 
1	much less my mind though thou should st add to tell
1	their sumptuous gluttonies and gorgeous feasts
1	on citron tables or atlantic stone
1	 for i have also heard perhaps have read 
1	their wines of setia cales and falerne 
1	chios and crete and how they quaff in gold 
1	crystal and myrrhine cups imbossed with gems
1	and studs of pearl to me should st tell who thirst
1	and hunger still then embassies thou shew st
1	from nations far and nigh what honour that 
1	but tedious waste of time to sit and hear
1	so many hollow compliments and lies 
1	outlandish flatteries then proceed st to talk
1	of the emperor how easily subdued 
1	how gloriously i shall thou say st expel
1	a brutish monster what if i withal
1	expel a devil who first made him such 
1	let his tormentor conscience find him out 
1	for him i was not sent nor yet to free
1	that people victor once now vile and base 
1	deservedly made vassal who once just 
1	frugal and mild and temperate conquered well 
1	but govern ill the nations under yoke 
1	peeling their provinces exhausted all
1	by lust and rapine first ambitious grown
1	of triumph that insulting vanity 
1	then cruel by their sports to blood inured
1	of fighting beasts and men to beasts exposed 
1	luxurious by their wealth and greedier still 
1	and from the daily scene effeminate 
1	what wise and valiant man would seek to free
1	these thus degenerate by themselves enslaved 
1	or could of inward slaves make outward free 
1	know therefore when my season comes to sit
1	on david s throne it shall be like a tree
1	spreading and overshadowing all the earth 
1	or as a stone that shall to pieces dash
1	all monarchies besides throughout the world 
1	and of my kingdom there shall be no end 
1	means there shall be to this but what the means
1	is not for thee to know nor me to tell 
1	to whom the tempter impudent replied 
1	 i see all offers made by me how slight
1	thou valuest because offered and reject st 
1	nothing will please the difficult and nice 
1	or nothing more than still to contradict 
1	on the other side know also thou that i
1	on what i offer set as high esteem 
1	nor what i part with mean to give for naught 
1	all these which in a moment thou behold st 
1	the kingdoms of the world to thee i give
1	 for given to me i give to whom i please 
1	no trifle yet with this reserve not else 
1	on this condition if thou wilt fall down 
1	and worship me as thy superior lord
1	 easily done and hold them all of me 
1	for what can less so great a gift deserve 
1	whom thus our saviour answered with disdain 
1	 i never liked thy talk thy offers less 
1	now both abhor since thou hast dared to utter
1	the abominable terms impious condition 
1	but i endure the time till which expired
1	thou hast permission on me it is written 
1	the first of all commandments thou shalt worship
1	the lord thy god and only him shalt serve 
1	and dar st thou to the son of god propound
1	to worship thee accursed now more accursed
1	for this attempt bolder than that on eve 
1	and more blasphemous which expect to rue 
1	the kingdoms of the world to thee were given 
1	permitted rather and by thee usurped 
1	other donation none thou canst produce 
1	if given by whom but by the king of kings 
1	god over all supreme if given to thee 
1	by thee how fairly is the giver now
1	repaid but gratitude in thee is lost
1	long since wert thou so void of fear or shame
1	as offer them to me the son of god 
1	to me my own on such abhorred pact 
1	that i fall down and worship thee as god 
1	get thee behind me plain thou now appear st
1	that evil one satan for ever damned 
1	to whom the fiend with fear abashed replied 
1	 be not so sore offended son of god 
1	though sons of god both angels are and men 
1	if i to try whether in higher sort
1	than these thou bear st that title have proposed
1	what both from men and angels i receive 
1	nations besides from all the quartered winds 
1	god of this world invoked and world beneath 
1	who then thou art whose coming is foretold
1	to me most fatal me it most concerns 
1	the trial hath indamaged thee no way 
1	rather more honour left and more esteem 
1	me naught advantaged missing what i aimed 
1	therefore let pass as they are transitory 
1	the kingdoms of this world i shall no more
1	advise thee gain them as thou canst or not 
1	and thou thyself seem st otherwise inclined
1	than to a worldly crown addicted more
1	to contemplation and profound dispute 
1	as by that early action may be judged 
1	when slipping from thy mother s eye thou went st
1	alone into the temple there wast found
1	among the gravest rabbies disputant
1	on points and questions fitting moses chair 
1	teaching not taught the childhood shews the man 
1	as morning shews the day be famous then 
1	by wisdom as thy empire must extend 
1	so let extend thy mind o er all the world
1	in knowledge all things in it comprehend 
1	all knowledge is not couched in moses law 
1	the pentateuch or what the prophets wrote 
1	the gentiles also know and write and teach
1	to admiration led by nature s light 
1	and with the gentiles much thou must converse 
1	ruling them by persuasion as thou mean st 
1	without their learning how wilt thou with them 
1	or they with thee hold conversation meet 
1	how wilt thou reason with them how refute
1	their idolisms traditions paradoxes 
1	error by his own arms is best evinced 
1	look once more ere we leave this specular mount 
1	westward much nearer by south west behold
1	where on the aegean shore a city stands 
1	built nobly pure the air and light the soil 
1	athens the eye of greece mother of arts
1	and eloquence native to famous wits
1	or hospitable in her sweet recess 
1	city or suburban studious walks and shades 
1	see there the olive grove of academe 
1	plato s retirement where the attic bird
1	trills her thick warbled notes the summer long 
1	there flowery hill hymettus with the sound
1	of bees industrious murmur oft invites
1	to studious musing there ilissus rowls
1	his whispering stream within the walls then view
1	the schools of ancient sages his who bred
1	great alexander to subdue the world 
1	there thou shalt hear and learn the secret power
1	of harmony in tones and numbers hit
1	by voice or hand and various measured verse 
1	aeolian charms and dorian lyric odes 
1	and his who gave them breath but higher sung 
1	blind melesigenes thence homer called 
1	whose poem phoebus challenged for his own 
1	thence what the lofty grave tragedians taught
1	in chorus or iambic teachers best
1	of moral prudence with delight received
1	in brief sententious precepts while they treat
1	of fate and chance and change in human life 
1	high actions and high passions best describing 
1	thence to the famous orators repair 
1	those ancient whose resistless eloquence
1	wielded at will that fierce democraty 
1	shook the arsenal and fulmined over greece
1	to macedon and artaxerxes throne 
1	to sage philosophy next lend thine ear 
1	from heaven descended to the low roofed house
1	of socrates see there his tenement 
1	whom well inspired the oracle pronounced
1	wisest of men from whose mouth issued forth
1	mellifluous streams that watered all the schools
1	of academics old and new with those
1	surnamed peripatetics and the sect
1	epicurean and the stoic severe 
1	these here revolve or as thou likest at home 
1	till time mature thee to a kingdom s weight 
1	these rules will render thee a king complete
1	within thyself much more with empire joined 
1	to whom our saviour sagely thus replied 
1	 think not but that i know these things or think
1	i know them not not therefore am i short
1	of knowing what i ought he who receives
1	light from above from the fountain of light 
1	no other doctrine needs though granted true 
1	but these are false or little else but dreams 
1	conjectures fancies built on nothing firm 
1	the first and wisest of them all professed
1	to know this only that he nothing knew 
1	the next to fabling fell and smooth conceits 
1	a third sort doubted all things though plain sense 
1	others in virtue placed felicity 
1	but virtue joined with riches and long life 
1	in corporal pleasure he and careless ease 
1	the stoic last in philosophic pride 
1	by him called virtue and his virtuous man 
1	wise perfect in himself and all possessing 
1	equal to god oft shames not to prefer 
1	as fearing god nor man contemning all
1	wealth pleasure pain or torment death and life 
1	which when he lists he leaves or boasts he can 
1	for all his tedious talk is but vain boast 
1	or subtle shifts conviction to evade 
1	alas what can they teach and not mislead 
1	ignorant of themselves of god much more 
1	and how the world began and how man fell 
1	degraded by himself on grace depending 
1	much of the soul they talk but all awry 
1	and in themselves seek virtue and to themselves
1	all glory arrogate to god give none 
1	rather accuse him under usual names 
1	fortune and fate as one regardless quite
1	of mortal things who therefore seeks in these
1	true wisdom finds her not or by delusion
1	far worse her false resemblance only meets 
1	an empty cloud however many books 
1	wise men have said are wearisome who reads
1	incessantly and to his reading brings not
1	a spirit and judgment equal or superior 
1	 and what he brings what needs he elsewhere seek 
1	uncertain and unsettled still remains 
1	deep versed in books and shallow in himself 
1	crude or intoxicate collecting toys
1	and trifles for choice matters worth a sponge 
1	as children gathering pebbles on the shore 
1	or if i would delight my private hours
1	with music or with poem where so soon
1	as in our native language can i find
1	that solace all our law and story strewed
1	with hymns our psalms with artful terms inscribed 
1	our hebrew songs and harps in babylon
1	that pleased so well our victor s ear declare
1	that rather greece from us these arts derived 
1	ill imitated while they loudest sing
1	the vices of their deities and their own 
1	in fable hymn or song so personating
1	their gods ridiculous and themselves past shame 
1	remove their swelling epithetes thick laid
1	as varnish on a harlot s cheek the rest 
1	thin sown with aught of profit or delight 
1	will far be found unworthy to compare
1	with sion s songs to all true tastes excelling 
1	where god is praised aright and godlike men 
1	 such are from god inspired not such from thee 
1	unless where moral virtue is expressed
1	by light of nature not in all quite lost 
1	their orators thou then extoll st as those
1	the top of eloquence statists indeed 
1	and lovers of their country as may seem 
1	but herein to our prophets far beneath 
1	as men divinely taught and better teaching
1	the solid rules of civil government 
1	in their majestic unaffected style 
1	than all the oratory of greece and rome 
1	in them is plainest taught and easiest learnt 
1	what makes a nation happy and keeps it so 
1	what ruins kingdoms and lays cities flat 
1	these only with our law best form a king 
1	so spake the son of god but satan now
1	quite at a loss for all his darts were spent 
1	thus to our saviour with stern brow replied 
1	 since neither wealth nor honour arms nor arts 
1	kingdom nor empire pleases thee nor aught
1	by me proposed in life contemplative
1	or active tended on by glory or fame 
1	what dost thou in this world the wilderness
1	for thee is fittest place i found thee there 
1	and thither will return thee yet remember
1	what i foretell thee soon thou shalt have cause
1	to wish thou never hadst rejected thus
1	nicely or cautiously my offered aid 
1	which would have set thee in short time with ease
1	on david s throne or throne of all the world 
1	now at full age fulness of time thy season 
1	when prophecies of thee are best fulfilled 
1	now contrary if i read aught in heaven 
1	or heaven write aught of fate by what the stars
1	voluminous or single characters
1	in their conjunction met give me to spell 
1	sorrows and labours opposition hate 
1	attends thee scorns reproaches injuries 
1	violence and stripes and lastly cruel death 
1	a kingdom they portend thee but what kingdom 
1	real or allegoric i discern not 
1	nor when eternal sure as without end 
1	without beginning for no date prefixed
1	directs me in the starry rubric set 
1	so saying he took for still he knew his power
1	not yet expired and to the wilderness
1	brought back the son of god and left him there 
1	feigning to disappear darkness now rose 
1	as daylight sunk and brought in louring night 
1	her shadowy offspring unsubstantial both 
1	privation mere of light and absent day 
1	our saviour meek and with untroubled mind
1	after hisaerie jaunt though hurried sore 
1	hungry and cold betook him to his rest 
1	wherever under some concourse of shades 
1	whose branching arms thick intertwined might shield
1	from dews and damps of night his sheltered head 
1	but sheltered slept in vain for at his head
1	the tempter watched and soon with ugly dreams
1	disturbed his sleep and either tropic now
1	 gan thunder and both ends of heaven the clouds
1	from many a horrid rift abortive poured
1	fierce rain with lightning mixed water with fire 
1	in ruin reconciled nor slept the winds
1	within their stony caves but rushed abroad
1	from the four hinges of the world and fell
1	on the vexed wilderness whose tallest pines 
1	though rooted deep as high and sturdiest oaks 
1	bowed their stiff necks loaden with stormy blasts 
1	or torn up sheer ill wast thou shrouded then 
1	o patient son of god yet only stood st
1	unshaken nor yet staid the terror there 
1	infernal ghosts and hellish furies round
1	environed thee some howled some yelled some shrieked 
1	some bent at thee their fiery darts while thou
1	sat st unappalled in calm and sinless peace 
1	thus passed the night so foul till morning fair
1	came forth with pilgrim steps in amice grey 
1	who with her radiant finger stilled the roar
1	of thunder chased the clouds and laid the winds 
1	and griesly spectres which the fiend had raised
1	to tempt the son of god with terrors dire 
1	and now the sun with more effectual beams
1	had cheered the face of earth and dried the wet
1	from drooping plant or dropping tree the birds 
1	who all things now behold more fresh and green 
1	after a night of storm so ruinous 
1	cleared up their choicest notes in bush and spray 
1	to gratulate the sweet return of morn 
1	nor yet amidst this joy and brightest morn 
1	was absent after all his mischief done 
1	the prince of darkness glad would also seem
1	of this fair change and to our saviour came 
1	yet with no new device they all were spent 
1	rather by this his last affront resolved 
1	desperate of better course to vent his rage
1	and mad despite to be so oft repelled 
1	him walking on a sunny hill he found 
1	backed on the north and west by a thick wood 
1	out of the wood he starts in wonted shape 
1	and in a careless mood thus to him said 
1	 fair morning yet betides thee son of god 
1	after a dismal night i heard the wrack 
1	as earth and sky would mingle but myself
1	was distant and these flaws though mortals fear them 
1	as dangerous to the pillared frame of heaven 
1	or to the earth s dark basis underneath 
1	are to the main as inconsiderable
1	and harmless if not wholesome as a sneeze
1	to man s less universe and soon are gone 
1	yet as being ofttimes noxious where they light
1	on man beast plant wasteful and turbulent 
1	like turbulencies in the affairs of men 
1	over whose heads they roar and seem to point 
1	they oft fore signify and threaten ill 
1	this tempest at this desert most was bent 
1	of men at thee for only thou here dwell st 
1	did i not tell thee if thou didst reject
1	the perfect season offered with my aid
1	to win thy destined seat but wilt prolong
1	all to the push of fate pursue thy way
1	of gaining david s throne no man knows when
1	 for both the when and how is nowhere told 
1	thou shalt be what thou art ordained no doubt 
1	for angels have proclaimed it but concealing
1	the time and means each act is rightliest done
1	not when it must but when it may be best 
1	if thou observe not this be sure to find
1	what i foretold thee many a hard assay
1	of dangers and adversities and pains 
1	ere thou of israel s sceptre get fast hold 
1	whereof this ominous night that closed thee round 
1	so many terrors voices prodigies 
1	may warn thee as a sure foregoing sign 
1	so talked he while the son of god went on 
1	and staid not but in brief him answered thus 
