1	a crew who under names of old renown 
1	osiris isis orus and their train 
1	with monstrous shapes and sorceries abused
1	their wandering gods disguised in brutish forms
1	rather than human nor did israel scape
1	th infection when their borrowed gold composed
1	the calf in oreb and the rebel king
1	doubled that sin in bethel and in dan 
1	likening his maker to the grazed ox 
1	jehovah who in one night when he passed
1	both her first born and all her bleating gods 
1	belial came last than whom a spirit more lewd
1	fell not from heaven or more gross to love
1	vice for itself to him no temple stood
1	or altar smoked yet who more oft than he
1	in temples and at altars when the priest
1	turns atheist as did eli s sons who filled
1	with lust and violence the house of god 
1	in courts and palaces he also reigns 
1	and in luxurious cities where the noise
1	of riot ascends above their loftiest towers 
1	and injury and outrage and when night
1	darkens the streets then wander forth the sons
1	of belial flown with insolence and wine 
1	witness the streets of sodom and that night
1	in gibeah when the hospitable door
1	exposed a matron to avoid worse rape 
1	these were the prime in order and in might 
1	the rest were long to tell though far renowned
1	th ionian gods of javan s issue held
1	gods yet confessed later than heaven and earth 
1	their boasted parents titan heaven s first born 
1	with his enormous brood and birthright seized
1	by younger saturn he from mightier jove 
1	his own and rhea s son like measure found 
1	so jove usurping reigned these first in crete
1	and ida known thence on the snowy top
1	of cold olympus ruled the middle air 
1	their highest heaven or on the delphian cliff 
1	or in dodona and through all the bounds
1	of doric land or who with saturn old
1	fled over adria to th hesperian fields 
1	and o er the celtic roamed the utmost isles 
1	all these and more came flocking but with looks
1	downcast and damp yet such wherein appeared
1	obscure some glimpse of joy to have found their chief
1	not in despair to have found themselves not lost
1	in loss itself which on his countenance cast
1	like doubtful hue but he his wonted pride
1	soon recollecting with high words that bore
1	semblance of worth not substance gently raised
1	their fainting courage and dispelled their fears 
1	then straight commands that at the warlike sound
1	of trumpets loud and clarions be upreared
1	his mighty standard that proud honour claimed
1	azazel as his right a cherub tall 
1	who forthwith from the glittering staff unfurled
1	th imperial ensign which full high advanced 
1	shone like a meteor streaming to the wind 
1	with gems and golden lustre rich emblazed 
1	seraphic arms and trophies all the while
1	sonorous metal blowing martial sounds 
1	at which the universal host up sent
1	a shout that tore hell s concave and beyond
1	frighted the reign of chaos and old night 
1	all in a moment through the gloom were seen
1	ten thousand banners rise into the air 
1	with orient colours waving with them rose
1	a forest huge of spears and thronging helms
1	appeared and serried shields in thick array
1	of depth immeasurable anon they move
1	in perfect phalanx to the dorian mood
1	of flutes and soft recorders such as raised
1	to height of noblest temper heroes old
1	arming to battle and instead of rage
1	deliberate valour breathed firm and unmoved
1	with dread of death to flight or foul retreat 
1	nor wanting power to mitigate and swage
1	with solemn touches troubled thoughts and chase
1	anguish and doubt and fear and sorrow and pain
1	from mortal or immortal minds thus they 
1	breathing united force with fixed thought 
1	moved on in silence to soft pipes that charmed
1	their painful steps o er the burnt soil and now
1	advanced in view they stand a horrid front
1	of dreadful length and dazzling arms in guise
1	of warriors old with ordered spear and shield 
1	awaiting what command their mighty chief
1	had to impose he through the armed files
1	darts his experienced eye and soon traverse
1	the whole battalion views their order due 
1	their visages and stature as of gods 
1	their number last he sums and now his heart
1	distends with pride and hardening in his strength 
1	glories for never since created man 
1	met such embodied force as named with these 
1	could merit more than that small infantry
1	warred on by cranes though all the giant brood
1	of phlegra with th heroic race were joined
1	that fought at thebes and ilium on each side
1	mixed with auxiliar gods and what resounds
1	in fable or romance of uther s son 
1	begirt with british and armoric knights 
1	and all who since baptized or infidel 
1	or whom biserta sent from afric shore
1	when charlemain with all his peerage fell
1	by fontarabbia thus far these beyond
1	compare of mortal prowess yet observed
1	their dread commander he above the rest
1	in shape and gesture proudly eminent 
1	stood like a tower his form had yet not lost
1	all her original brightness nor appeared
1	less than archangel ruined and th excess
1	of glory obscured as when the sun new risen
1	looks through the horizontal misty air
1	shorn of his beams or from behind the moon 
1	in dim eclipse disastrous twilight sheds
1	on half the nations and with fear of change
1	perplexes monarchs darkened so yet shone
1	above them all th archangel but his face
1	deep scars of thunder had intrenched and care
1	sat on his faded cheek but under brows
1	of dauntless courage and considerate pride
1	waiting revenge cruel his eye but cast
1	signs of remorse and passion to behold
1	the fellows of his crime the followers rather
1	 far other once beheld in bliss condemned
1	for ever now to have their lot in pain 
1	millions of spirits for his fault amerced
1	of heaven and from eternal splendours flung
1	for his revolt yet faithful how they stood 
1	their glory withered as when heaven s fire
1	hath scathed the forest oaks or mountain pines 
1	with singed top their stately growth though bare 
1	stands on the blasted heath he now prepared
1	to speak whereat their doubled ranks they bend
1	from wing to wing and half enclose him round
1	with all his peers attention held them mute 
1	thrice he assayed and thrice in spite of scorn 
1	tears such as angels weep burst forth at last
1	words interwove with sighs found out their way 
1	 o myriads of immortal spirits o powers
1	matchless but with th almighty and that strife
1	was not inglorious though th event was dire 
1	as this place testifies and this dire change 
1	hateful to utter but what power of mind 
1	forseeing or presaging from the depth
1	of knowledge past or present could have feared
1	how such united force of gods how such
1	as stood like these could ever know repulse 
1	for who can yet believe though after loss 
1	that all these puissant legions whose exile
1	hath emptied heaven shall fail to re ascend 
1	self raised and repossess their native seat 
1	for me be witness all the host of heaven 
1	if counsels different or danger shunned
1	by me have lost our hopes but he who reigns
1	monarch in heaven till then as one secure
1	sat on his throne upheld by old repute 
1	consent or custom and his regal state
1	put forth at full but still his strength concealed 
1	which tempted our attempt and wrought our fall 
1	henceforth his might we know and know our own 
1	so as not either to provoke or dread
1	new war provoked our better part remains
1	to work in close design by fraud or guile 
1	what force effected not that he no less
1	at length from us may find who overcomes
1	by force hath overcome but half his foe 
1	space may produce new worlds whereof so rife
1	there went a fame in heaven that he ere long
1	intended to create and therein plant
1	a generation whom his choice regard
1	should favour equal to the sons of heaven 
1	thither if but to pry shall be perhaps
1	our first eruption thither or elsewhere 
1	for this infernal pit shall never hold
1	celestial spirits in bondage nor th abyss
1	long under darkness cover but these thoughts
1	full counsel must mature peace is despaired 
1	for who can think submission war then war
1	open or understood must be resolved 
1	he spake and to confirm his words outflew
1	millions of flaming swords drawn from the thighs
1	of mighty cherubim the sudden blaze
1	far round illumined hell highly they raged
1	against the highest and fierce with grasped arms
1	clashed on their sounding shields the din of war 
1	hurling defiance toward the vault of heaven 
1	there stood a hill not far whose grisly top
1	belched fire and rolling smoke the rest entire
1	shone with a glossy scurf undoubted sign
1	that in his womb was hid metallic ore 
1	the work of sulphur thither winged with speed 
1	a numerous brigade hastened as when bands
1	forerun the royal camp to trench a field 
1	or cast a rampart mammon led them on 
1	mammon the least erected spirit that fell
1	from heaven for even in heaven his looks and thoughts
1	were always downward bent admiring more
1	the riches of heaven s pavement trodden gold 
1	than aught divine or holy else enjoyed
1	in vision beatific by him first
1	men also and by his suggestion taught 
1	ransacked the centre and with impious hands
1	rifled the bowels of their mother earth
1	for treasures better hid soon had his crew
1	opened into the hill a spacious wound 
1	and digged out ribs of gold let none admire
1	that riches grow in hell that soil may best
1	deserve the precious bane and here let those
1	who boast in mortal things and wondering tell
1	of babel and the works of memphian kings 
1	learn how their greatest monuments of fame
1	and strength and art are easily outdone
1	by spirits reprobate and in an hour
1	what in an age they with incessant toil
1	and hands innumerable scarce perform 
1	nigh on the plain in many cells prepared 
1	that underneath had veins of liquid fire
1	sluiced from the lake a second multitude
1	with wondrous art founded the massy ore 
1	severing each kind and scummed the bullion dross 
1	a third as soon had formed within the ground
1	a various mould and from the boiling cells
1	by strange conveyance filled each hollow nook 
1	as in an organ from one blast of wind 
1	to many a row of pipes the sound board breathes 
1	anon out of the earth a fabric huge
1	rose like an exhalation with the sound
1	of dulcet symphonies and voices sweet 
