1	from heaven s high jurisdiction in new league
1	banded against his throne but to remain
1	in strictest bondage though thus far removed 
1	under th inevitable curb reserved
1	his captive multitude for he to be sure 
1	in height or depth still first and last will reign
1	sole king and of his kingdom lose no part
1	by our revolt but over hell extend
1	his empire and with iron sceptre rule
1	us here as with his golden those in heaven 
1	what sit we then projecting peace and war 
1	war hath determined us and foiled with loss
1	irreparable terms of peace yet none
1	vouchsafed or sought for what peace will be given
1	to us enslaved but custody severe 
1	and stripes and arbitrary punishment
1	inflicted and what peace can we return 
1	but to our power hostility and hate 
1	untamed reluctance and revenge though slow 
1	yet ever plotting how the conqueror least
1	may reap his conquest and may least rejoice
1	in doing what we most in suffering feel 
1	nor will occasion want nor shall we need
1	with dangerous expedition to invade
1	heaven whose high walls fear no assault or siege 
1	or ambush from the deep what if we find
1	some easier enterprise there is a place
1	 if ancient and prophetic fame in heaven
1	err not another world the happy seat
1	of some new race called man about this time
1	to be created like to us though less
1	in power and excellence but favoured more
1	of him who rules above so was his will
1	pronounced among the gods and by an oath
1	that shook heaven s whole circumference confirmed 
1	thither let us bend all our thoughts to learn
1	what creatures there inhabit of what mould
1	or substance how endued and what their power
1	and where their weakness how attempted best 
1	by force of subtlety though heaven be shut 
1	and heaven s high arbitrator sit secure
1	in his own strength this place may lie exposed 
1	the utmost border of his kingdom left
1	to their defence who hold it here perhaps 
1	some advantageous act may be achieved
1	by sudden onset either with hell fire
1	to waste his whole creation or possess
1	all as our own and drive as we were driven 
1	the puny habitants or if not drive 
1	seduce them to our party that their god
1	may prove their foe and with repenting hand
1	abolish his own works this would surpass
1	common revenge and interrupt his joy
1	in our confusion and our joy upraise
1	in his disturbance when his darling sons 
1	hurled headlong to partake with us shall curse
1	their frail original and faded bliss 
1	faded so soon advise if this be worth
1	attempting or to sit in darkness here
1	hatching vain empires thus beelzebub
1	pleaded his devilish counsel first devised
1	by satan and in part proposed for whence 
1	but from the author of all ill could spring
1	so deep a malice to confound the race
1	of mankind in one root and earth with hell
1	to mingle and involve done all to spite
1	the great creator but their spite still serves
1	his glory to augment the bold design
1	pleased highly those infernal states and joy
1	sparkled in all their eyes with full assent
1	they vote whereat his speech he thus renews 
1	 well have ye judged well ended long debate 
1	synod of gods and like to what ye are 
1	great things resolved which from the lowest deep
1	will once more lift us up in spite of fate 
1	nearer our ancient seat perhaps in view
1	of those bright confines whence with neighbouring arms 
1	and opportune excursion we may chance
1	re enter heaven or else in some mild zone
1	dwell not unvisited of heaven s fair light 
1	secure and at the brightening orient beam
1	purge off this gloom the soft delicious air 
1	to heal the scar of these corrosive fires 
1	shall breathe her balm but first whom shall we send
1	in search of this new world whom shall we find
1	sufficient who shall tempt with wandering feet
1	the dark unbottomed infinite abyss 
1	and through the palpable obscure find out
1	his uncouth way or spread his airy flight 
1	upborne with indefatigable wings
1	over the vast abrupt ere he arrive
1	the happy isle what strength what art can then
1	suffice or what evasion bear him safe 
1	through the strict senteries and stations thick
1	of angels watching round here he had need
1	all circumspection and we now no less
1	choice in our suffrage for on whom we send
1	the weight of all and our last hope relies 
1	this said he sat and expectation held
1	his look suspense awaiting who appeared
1	to second or oppose or undertake
1	the perilous attempt but all sat mute 
1	pondering the danger with deep thoughts and each
1	in other s countenance read his own dismay 
1	astonished none among the choice and prime
1	of those heaven warring champions could be found
1	so hardy as to proffer or accept 
1	alone the dreadful voyage till at last 
1	satan whom now transcendent glory raised
1	above his fellows with monarchal pride
1	conscious of highest worth unmoved thus spake 
1	with reason hath deep silence and demur
1	seized us though undismayed long is the way
1	and hard that out of hell leads up to light 
1	our prison strong this huge convex of fire 
1	outrageous to devour immures us round
1	ninefold and gates of burning adamant 
1	barred over us prohibit all egress 
1	these passed if any pass the void profound
1	of unessential night receives him next 
1	wide gaping and with utter loss of being
1	threatens him plunged in that abortive gulf 
1	if thence he scape into whatever world 
1	or unknown region what remains him less
1	than unknown dangers and as hard escape 
1	but i should ill become this throne o peers 
1	and this imperial sovereignty adorned
1	with splendour armed with power if aught proposed
1	and judged of public moment in the shape
1	of difficulty or danger could deter
1	me from attempting wherefore do i assume
1	these royalties and not refuse to reign 
1	refusing to accept as great a share
1	of hazard as of honour due alike
1	to him who reigns and so much to him due
1	of hazard more as he above the rest
1	high honoured sits go therefore mighty powers 
1	terror of heaven though fallen intend at home 
1	while here shall be our home what best may ease
1	the present misery and render hell
1	more tolerable if there be cure or charm
1	to respite or deceive or slack the pain
1	of this ill mansion intermit no watch
1	against a wakeful foe while i abroad
1	through all the coasts of dark destruction seek
1	deliverance for us all this enterprise
1	none shall partake with me thus saying rose
1	the monarch and prevented all reply 
1	prudent lest from his resolution raised 
1	others among the chief might offer now 
1	certain to be refused what erst they feared 
1	and so refused might in opinion stand
1	his rivals winning cheap the high repute
1	which he through hazard huge must earn but they
1	dreaded not more th adventure than his voice
1	forbidding and at once with him they rose 
1	their rising all at once was as the sound
1	of thunder heard remote towards him they bend
1	with awful reverence prone and as a god
1	extol him equal to the highest in heaven 
1	nor failed they to express how much they praised
1	that for the general safety he despised
1	his own for neither do the spirits damned
1	lose all their virtue lest bad men should boast
1	their specious deeds on earth which glory excites 
1	or close ambition varnished o er with zeal 
1	thus they their doubtful consultations dark
1	ended rejoicing in their matchless chief 
1	as when from mountain tops the dusky clouds
1	ascending while the north wind sleeps o erspread
1	heaven s cheerful face the louring element
1	scowls o er the darkened landscape snow or shower 
1	if chance the radiant sun with farewell sweet 
1	extend his evening beam the fields revive 
1	the birds their notes renew and bleating herds
1	attest their joy that hill and valley rings 
1	o shame to men devil with devil damned
1	firm concord holds men only disagree
1	of creatures rational though under hope
1	of heavenly grace and god proclaiming peace 
1	yet live in hatred enmity and strife
1	among themselves and levy cruel wars
1	wasting the earth each other to destroy 
1	as if which might induce us to accord 
1	man had not hellish foes enow besides 
1	that day and night for his destruction wait 
1	the stygian council thus dissolved and forth
1	in order came the grand infernal peers 
1	midst came their mighty paramount and seemed
1	alone th antagonist of heaven nor less
1	than hell s dread emperor with pomp supreme 
1	and god like imitated state him round
1	a globe of fiery seraphim enclosed
1	with bright emblazonry and horrent arms 
1	then of their session ended they bid cry
1	with trumpet s regal sound the great result 
1	toward the four winds four speedy cherubim
1	put to their mouths the sounding alchemy 
1	by herald s voice explained the hollow abyss
1	heard far and wide and all the host of hell
1	with deafening shout returned them loud acclaim 
1	thence more at ease their minds and somewhat raised
1	by false presumptuous hope the ranged powers
1	disband and wandering each his several way
1	pursues as inclination or sad choice
1	leads him perplexed where he may likeliest find
1	truce to his restless thoughts and entertain
1	the irksome hours till his great chief return 
1	part on the plain or in the air sublime 
1	upon the wing or in swift race contend 
1	as at th olympian games or pythian fields 
1	part curb their fiery steeds or shun the goal
1	with rapid wheels or fronted brigades form 
1	as when to warn proud cities war appears
1	waged in the troubled sky and armies rush
1	to battle in the clouds before each van
1	prick forth the airy knights and couch their spears 
1	till thickest legions close with feats of arms
1	from either end of heaven the welkin burns 
1	others with vast typhoean rage more fell 
1	rend up both rocks and hills and ride the air
1	in whirlwind hell scarce holds the wild uproar 
1	as when alcides from oechalia crowned
1	with conquest felt th envenomed robe and tore
1	through pain up by the roots thessalian pines 
1	and lichas from the top of oeta threw
