1	on high behests his angels to and fro
1	passed frequent and his eye with choice regard
1	from paneas the fount of jordan s flood 
1	to beersaba where the holy land
1	so wide the opening seemed where bounds were set
1	to darkness such as bound the ocean wave 
1	satan from hence now on the lower stair 
1	that scaled by steps of gold to heaven gate 
1	looks down with wonder at the sudden view
1	of all this world at once as when a scout 
1	through dark and desert ways with peril gone
1	all night at last by break of cheerful dawn
1	obtains the brow of some high climbing hill 
1	which to his eye discovers unaware
1	the goodly prospect of some foreign land
1	first seen or some renowned metropolis
1	with glistering spires and pinnacles adorned 
1	which now the rising sun gilds with his beams 
1	such wonder seised though after heaven seen 
1	the spirit malign but much more envy seised 
1	at sight of all this world beheld so fair 
1	round he surveys and well might where he stood
1	so high above the circling canopy
1	of night s extended shade from eastern point
1	of libra to the fleecy star that bears
1	andromeda far off atlantick seas
1	beyond the horizon then from pole to pole
1	he views in breadth and without longer pause
1	down right into the world s first region throws
1	his flight precipitant and winds with ease
1	through the pure marble air his oblique way
1	amongst innumerable stars that shone
1	stars distant but nigh hand seemed other worlds 
1	or other worlds they seemed or happy isles 
1	like those hesperian gardens famed of old 
1	fortunate fields and groves and flowery vales 
1	thrice happy isles but who dwelt happy there
1	he staid not to inquire above them all
1	the golden sun in splendour likest heaven 
1	allured his eye thither his course he bends
1	through the calm firmament but up or down 
1	by center or eccentrick hard to tell 
1	or longitude where the great luminary
1	aloof the vulgar constellations thick 
1	that from his lordly eye keep distance due 
1	dispenses light from far they as they move
1	their starry dance in numbers that compute
1	days months and years towards his all cheering lamp
1	turn swift their various motions or are turned
1	by his magnetick beam that gently warms
1	the universe and to each inward part
1	with gentle penetration though unseen 
1	shoots invisible virtue even to the deep 
1	so wonderously was set his station bright 
1	there lands the fiend a spot like which perhaps
1	astronomer in the sun s lucent orb
1	through his glazed optick tube yet never saw 
1	the place he found beyond expression bright 
1	compared with aught on earth metal or stone 
1	not all parts like but all alike informed
1	with radiant light as glowing iron with fire 
1	if metal part seemed gold part silver clear 
1	if stone carbuncle most or chrysolite 
1	ruby or topaz to the twelve that shone
1	in aaron s breast plate and a stone besides
1	imagined rather oft than elsewhere seen 
1	that stone or like to that which here below
1	philosophers in vain so long have sought 
1	in vain though by their powerful art they bind
1	volatile hermes and call up unbound
1	in various shapes old proteus from the sea 
1	drained through a limbeck to his native form 
1	what wonder then if fields and regions here
1	breathe forth elixir pure and rivers run
1	potable gold when with one virtuous touch
1	the arch chemick sun so far from us remote 
1	produces with terrestrial humour mixed 
1	here in the dark so many precious things
1	of colour glorious and effect so rare 
1	here matter new to gaze the devil met
1	undazzled far and wide his eye commands 
1	for sight no obstacle found here nor shade 
1	but all sun shine as when his beams at noon
1	culminate from the equator as they now
1	shot upward still direct whence no way round
1	shadow from body opaque can fall and the air 
1	no where so clear sharpened his visual ray
1	to objects distant far whereby he soon
1	saw within ken a glorious angel stand 
1	the same whom john saw also in the sun 
1	his back was turned but not his brightness hid 
1	of beaming sunny rays a golden tiar
1	circled his head nor less his locks behind
1	illustrious on his shoulders fledge with wings
1	lay waving round on some great charge employed
1	he seemed or fixed in cogitation deep 
1	glad was the spirit impure as now in hope
1	to find who might direct his wandering flight
1	to paradise the happy seat of man 
1	his journey s end and our beginning woe 
1	but first he casts to change his proper shape 
1	which else might work him danger or delay 
1	and now a stripling cherub he appears 
1	not of the prime yet such as in his face
1	youth smiled celestial and to every limb
1	suitable grace diffused so well he feigned 
1	under a coronet his flowing hair
1	in curls on either cheek played wings he wore
1	of many a coloured plume sprinkled with gold 
1	his habit fit for speed succinct and held
1	before his decent steps a silver wand 
1	he drew not nigh unheard the angel bright 
1	ere he drew nigh his radiant visage turned 
1	admonished by his ear and straight was known
1	the arch angel uriel one of the seven
1	who in god s presence nearest to his throne 
1	stand ready at command and are his eyes
1	that run through all the heavens or down to the earth
1	bear his swift errands over moist and dry 
1	o er sea and land him satan thus accosts 
1	uriel for thou of those seven spirits that stand
1	in sight of god s high throne gloriously bright 
1	the first art wont his great authentick will
1	interpreter through highest heaven to bring 
1	where all his sons thy embassy attend 
1	and here art likeliest by supreme decree
1	like honour to obtain and as his eye
1	to visit oft this new creation round 
1	unspeakable desire to see and know
1	all these his wonderous works but chiefly man 
1	his chief delight and favour him for whom
1	all these his works so wonderous he ordained 
1	hath brought me from the quires of cherubim
1	alone thus wandering brightest seraph tell
1	in which of all these shining orbs hath man
1	his fixed seat or fixed seat hath none 
1	but all these shining orbs his choice to dwell 
1	that i may find him and with secret gaze
1	or open admiration him behold 
1	on whom the great creator hath bestowed
1	worlds and on whom hath all these graces poured 
1	that both in him and all things as is meet 
1	the universal maker we may praise 
1	who justly hath driven out his rebel foes
1	to deepest hell and to repair that loss 
1	created this new happy race of men
1	to serve him better wise are all his ways 
1	so spake the false dissembler unperceived 
1	for neither man nor angel can discern
1	hypocrisy the only evil that walks
1	invisible except to god alone 
1	by his permissive will through heaven and earth 
1	and oft though wisdom wake suspicion sleeps
1	at wisdom s gate and to simplicity
1	resigns her charge while goodness thinks no ill
1	where no ill seems which now for once beguiled
1	uriel though regent of the sun and held
1	the sharpest sighted spirit of all in heaven 
1	who to the fraudulent impostor foul 
1	in his uprightness answer thus returned 
1	fair angel thy desire which tends to know
1	the works of god thereby to glorify
1	the great work master leads to no excess
1	that reaches blame but rather merits praise
1	the more it seems excess that led thee hither
1	from thy empyreal mansion thus alone 
1	to witness with thine eyes what some perhaps 
1	contented with report hear only in heaven 
1	for wonderful indeed are all his works 
1	pleasant to know and worthiest to be all
1	had in remembrance always with delight 
1	but what created mind can comprehend
1	their number or the wisdom infinite
1	that brought them forth but hid their causes deep 
1	i saw when at his word the formless mass 
1	this world s material mould came to a heap 
1	confusion heard his voice and wild uproar
1	stood ruled stood vast infinitude confined 
1	till at his second bidding darkness fled 
1	light shone and order from disorder sprung 
1	swift to their several quarters hasted then
1	the cumbrous elements earth flood air fire 
1	and this ethereal quintessence of heaven
1	flew upward spirited with various forms 
1	that rolled orbicular and turned to stars
1	numberless as thou seest and how they move 
1	each had his place appointed each his course 
1	the rest in circuit walls this universe 
1	look downward on that globe whose hither side
1	with light from hence though but reflected shines 
1	that place is earth the seat of man that light
1	his day which else as the other hemisphere 
1	night would invade but there the neighbouring moon
1	 so call that opposite fair star her aid
1	timely interposes and her monthly round
1	still ending still renewing through mid heaven 
1	with borrowed light her countenance triform
1	hence fills and empties to enlighten the earth 
1	and in her pale dominion checks the night 
1	that spot to which i point is paradise 
1	adam s abode those lofty shades his bower 
1	thy way thou canst not miss me mine requires 
1	thus said he turned and satan bowing low 
1	as to superiour spirits is wont in heaven 
1	where honour due and reverence none neglects 
1	took leave and toward the coast of earth beneath 
1	down from the ecliptick sped with hoped success 
1	throws his steep flight in many an aery wheel 
1	nor staid till on niphates top he lights 
1	o for that warning voice which he who saw
1	the apocalypse heard cry in heaven aloud 
1	then when the dragon put to second rout 
1	came furious down to be revenged on men 
1	woe to the inhabitants on earth that now 
1	while time was our first parents had been warned
1	the coming of their secret foe and scaped 
1	haply so scaped his mortal snare for now
1	satan now first inflamed with rage came down 
1	the tempter ere the accuser of mankind 
1	to wreak on innocent frail man his loss
1	of that first battle and his flight to hell 
1	yet not rejoicing in his speed though bold
1	far off and fearless nor with cause to boast 
1	begins his dire attempt which nigh the birth
1	now rolling boils in his tumultuous breast 
1	and like a devilish engine back recoils
1	upon himself horrour and doubt distract
1	his troubled thoughts and from the bottom stir
1	the hell within him for within him hell
1	he brings and round about him nor from hell
1	one step no more than from himself can fly
1	by change of place now conscience wakes despair 
1	that slumbered wakes the bitter memory
1	of what he was what is and what must be
1	worse of worse deeds worse sufferings must ensue 
1	sometimes towards eden which now in his view
1	lay pleasant his grieved look he fixes sad 
1	sometimes towards heaven and the full blazing sun 
1	which now sat high in his meridian tower 
1	then much revolving thus in sighs began 
1	o thou that with surpassing glory crowned 
1	lookest from thy sole dominion like the god
1	of this new world at whose sight all the stars
1	hide their diminished heads to thee i call 
1	but with no friendly voice and add thy name 
1	of sun to tell thee how i hate thy beams 
1	that bring to my remembrance from what state
1	i fell how glorious once above thy sphere 
1	till pride and worse ambition threw me down
1	warring in heaven against heaven s matchless king 
1	ah wherefore he deserved no such return
1	from me whom he created what i was
1	in that bright eminence and with his good
1	upbraided none nor was his service hard 
1	what could be less than to afford him praise 
1	the easiest recompence and pay him thanks 
1	how due yet all his good proved ill in me 
1	and wrought but malice lifted up so high
1	i sdeined subjection and thought one step higher
1	would set me highest and in a moment quit
1	the debt immense of endless gratitude 
1	so burdensome still paying still to owe 
1	forgetful what from him i still received 
1	and understood not that a grateful mind
1	by owing owes not but still pays at once
1	indebted and discharged what burden then
1	o had his powerful destiny ordained
1	me some inferiour angel i had stood
1	then happy no unbounded hope had raised
1	ambition yet why not some other power
1	as great might have aspired and me though mean 
1	drawn to his part but other powers as great
1	fell not but stand unshaken from within
1	or from without to all temptations armed 
1	hadst thou the same free will and power to stand 
1	thou hadst whom hast thou then or what to accuse 
1	but heaven s free love dealt equally to all 
1	be then his love accursed since love or hate 
1	to me alike it deals eternal woe 
1	nay cursed be thou since against his thy will
1	chose freely what it now so justly rues 
1	me miserable which way shall i fly
1	infinite wrath and infinite despair 
1	which way i fly is hell myself am hell 
1	and in the lowest deep a lower deep
1	still threatening to devour me opens wide 
1	to which the hell i suffer seems a heaven 
1	o then at last relent is there no place
1	left for repentance none for pardon left 
1	none left but by submission and that word
1	disdain forbids me and my dread of shame
1	among the spirits beneath whom i seduced
1	with other promises and other vaunts
1	than to submit boasting i could subdue
1	the omnipotent ay me they little know
1	how dearly i abide that boast so vain 
1	under what torments inwardly i groan 
1	while they adore me on the throne of hell 
1	with diadem and scepter high advanced 
1	the lower still i fall only supreme
1	in misery such joy ambition finds 
1	but say i could repent and could obtain 
1	by act of grace my former state how soon
1	would highth recall high thoughts how soon unsay
1	what feigned submission swore ease would recant
1	vows made in pain as violent and void 
1	for never can true reconcilement grow 
1	where wounds of deadly hate have pierced so deep 
1	which would but lead me to a worse relapse
1	and heavier fall so should i purchase dear
1	short intermission bought with double smart 
1	this knows my punisher therefore as far
1	from granting he as i from begging peace 
1	all hope excluded thus behold instead
1	of us out cast exil d his new delight 
1	mankind created and for him this world 
1	so farewell hope and with hope farewell fear 
1	farewell remorse all good to me is lost 
1	evil be thou my good by thee at least
1	divided empire with heaven s king i hold 
1	by thee and more than half perhaps will reign 
1	as man ere long and this new world shall know 
1	thus while he spake each passion dimmed his face
1	thrice changed with pale ire envy and despair 
1	which marred his borrowed visage and betrayed
1	him counterfeit if any eye beheld 
1	for heavenly minds from such distempers foul
1	are ever clear whereof he soon aware 
1	each perturbation smoothed with outward calm 
1	artificer of fraud and was the first
1	that practised falsehood under saintly show 
1	deep malice to conceal couched with revenge 
1	yet not enough had practised to deceive
1	uriel once warned whose eye pursued him down
1	the way he went and on the assyrian mount
1	saw him disfigured more than could befall
1	spirit of happy sort his gestures fierce
1	he marked and mad demeanour then alone 
1	as he supposed all unobserved unseen 
1	so on he fares and to the border comes
1	of eden where delicious paradise 
1	now nearer crowns with her enclosure green 
1	as with a rural mound the champaign head
1	of a steep wilderness whose hairy sides
1	with thicket overgrown grotesque and wild 
1	access denied and overhead upgrew
1	insuperable height of loftiest shade 
1	cedar and pine and fir and branching palm 
1	a sylvan scene and as the ranks ascend 
1	shade above shade a woody theatre
1	of stateliest view yet higher than their tops
1	the verdurous wall of paradise upsprung 
1	which to our general sire gave prospect large
1	into his nether empire neighbouring round 
1	and higher than that wall a circling row
1	of goodliest trees loaden with fairest fruit 
1	blossoms and fruits at once of golden hue 
1	appeared with gay enamelled colours mixed 
1	on which the sun more glad impressed his beams
1	than in fair evening cloud or humid bow 
1	when god hath showered the earth so lovely seemed
1	that landskip and of pure now purer air
1	meets his approach and to the heart inspires
1	vernal delight and joy able to drive
1	all sadness but despair now gentle gales 
1	fanning their odoriferous wings dispense
1	native perfumes and whisper whence they stole
1	those balmy spoils as when to them who fail
1	beyond the cape of hope and now are past
1	mozambick off at sea north east winds blow
1	sabean odours from the spicy shore
1	of araby the blest with such delay
1	well pleased they slack their course and many a league
1	cheered with the grateful smell old ocean smiles 
1	so entertained those odorous sweets the fiend 
1	who came their bane though with them better pleased
1	than asmodeus with the fishy fume
1	that drove him though enamoured from the spouse
1	of tobit s son and with a vengeance sent
1	now to the ascent of that steep savage hill
1	satan had journeyed on pensive and slow 
1	but further way found none so thick entwined 
1	as one continued brake the undergrowth
1	of shrubs and tangling bushes had perplexed
1	all path of man or beast that passed that way 
1	one gate there only was and that looked east
1	on the other side which when the arch felon saw 
1	due entrance he disdained and in contempt 
1	at one flight bound high over leaped all bound
1	of hill or highest wall and sheer within
1	lights on his feet as when a prowling wolf 
1	whom hunger drives to seek new haunt for prey 
1	watching where shepherds pen their flocks at eve
1	in hurdled cotes amid the field secure 
1	leaps o er the fence with ease into the fold 
1	or as a thief bent to unhoard the cash
1	of some rich burgher whose substantial doors 
1	cross barred and bolted fast fear no assault 
1	in at the window climbs or o er the tiles 
1	so clomb this first grand thief into god s fold 
1	so since into his church lewd hirelings climb 
1	thence up he flew and on the tree of life 
1	the middle tree and highest there that grew 
1	sat like a cormorant yet not true life
1	thereby regained but sat devising death
1	to them who lived nor on the virtue thought
1	of that life giving plant but only used
1	for prospect what well used had been the pledge
1	of immortality so little knows
1	any but god alone to value right
1	the good before him but perverts best things
1	to worst abuse or to their meanest use 
1	beneath him with new wonder now he views 
1	to all delight of human sense exposed 
1	in narrow room nature s whole wealth yea more 
1	a heaven on earth for blissful paradise
1	of god the garden was by him in the east
1	of eden planted eden stretched her line
1	from auran eastward to the royal towers
1	of great seleucia built by grecian kings 
1	or where the sons of eden long before
1	dwelt in telassar in this pleasant soil
1	his far more pleasant garden god ordained 
1	out of the fertile ground he caused to grow
1	all trees of noblest kind for sight smell taste 
1	and all amid them stood the tree of life 
1	high eminent blooming ambrosial fruit
1	of vegetable gold and next to life 
1	our death the tree of knowledge grew fast by 
1	knowledge of good bought dear by knowing ill 
1	southward through eden went a river large 
1	nor changed his course but through the shaggy hill
1	passed underneath ingulfed for god had thrown
1	that mountain as his garden mould high raised
1	upon the rapid current which through veins
1	of porous earth with kindly thirst up drawn 
1	rose a fresh fountain and with many a rill
1	watered the garden thence united fell
1	down the steep glade and met the nether flood 
1	which from his darksome passage now appears 
1	and now divided into four main streams 
1	runs diverse wandering many a famous realm
1	and country whereof here needs no account 
1	but rather to tell how if art could tell 
1	how from that sapphire fount the crisped brooks 
1	rolling on orient pearl and sands of gold 
1	with mazy errour under pendant shades
1	ran nectar visiting each plant and fed
1	flowers worthy of paradise which not nice art
1	in beds and curious knots but nature boon
1	poured forth profuse on hill and dale and plain 
1	both where the morning sun first warmly smote
1	the open field and where the unpierced shade
1	imbrowned the noontide bowers thus was this place
1	a happy rural seat of various view 
1	groves whose rich trees wept odorous gums and balm 
1	others whose fruit burnished with golden rind 
1	hung amiable hesperian fables true 
1	if true here only and of delicious taste 
1	betwixt them lawns or level downs and flocks
1	grazing the tender herb were interposed 
1	or palmy hillock or the flowery lap
1	of some irriguous valley spread her store 
1	flowers of all hue and without thorn the rose 
1	another side umbrageous grots and caves
1	of cool recess o er which the mantling vine
1	lays forth her purple grape and gently creeps
1	luxuriant mean while murmuring waters fall
1	down the slope hills dispersed or in a lake 
1	that to the fringed bank with myrtle crowned
1	her crystal mirrour holds unite their streams 
1	the birds their quire apply airs vernal airs 
1	breathing the smell of field and grove attune
1	the trembling leaves while universal pan 
1	knit with the graces and the hours in dance 
1	led on the eternal spring not that fair field
1	of enna where proserpine gathering flowers 
1	herself a fairer flower by gloomy dis
1	was gathered which cost ceres all that pain
1	to seek her through the world nor that sweet grove
1	of daphne by orontes and the inspired
1	castalian spring might with this paradise
1	of eden strive nor that nyseian isle
1	girt with the river triton where old cham 
1	whom gentiles ammon call and libyan jove 
1	hid amalthea and her florid son
1	young bacchus from his stepdame rhea s eye 
1	nor where abassin kings their issue guard 
1	mount amara though this by some supposed
1	true paradise under the ethiop line
1	by nilus head enclosed with shining rock 
1	a whole day s journey high but wide remote
1	from this assyrian garden where the fiend
1	saw undelighted all delight all kind
1	of living creatures new to sight and strange
1	two of far nobler shape erect and tall 
1	godlike erect with native honour clad
1	in naked majesty seemed lords of all 
1	and worthy seemed for in their looks divine
1	the image of their glorious maker shone 
1	truth wisdom sanctitude severe and pure 
1	 severe but in true filial freedom placed 
1	whence true authority in men though both
1	not equal as their sex not equal seemed 
1	for contemplation he and valour formed 
1	for softness she and sweet attractive grace 
1	he for god only she for god in him 
1	his fair large front and eye sublime declared
1	absolute rule and hyacinthine locks
1	round from his parted forelock manly hung
1	clustering but not beneath his shoulders broad 
1	she as a veil down to the slender waist
1	her unadorned golden tresses wore
1	dishevelled but in wanton ringlets waved
1	as the vine curls her tendrils which implied
1	subjection but required with gentle sway 
1	and by her yielded by him best received 
1	yielded with coy submission modest pride 
1	and sweet reluctant amorous delay 
1	nor those mysterious parts were then concealed 
1	then was not guilty shame dishonest shame
1	of nature s works honour dishonourable 
1	sin bred how have ye troubled all mankind
1	with shows instead mere shows of seeming pure 
1	and banished from man s life his happiest life 
1	simplicity and spotless innocence 
1	so passed they naked on nor shunned the sight
1	of god or angel for they thought no ill 
1	so hand in hand they passed the loveliest pair 
1	that ever since in love s embraces met 
1	adam the goodliest man of men since born
1	his sons the fairest of her daughters eve 
1	under a tuft of shade that on a green
1	stood whispering soft by a fresh fountain side
1	they sat them down and after no more toil
1	of their sweet gardening labour than sufficed
1	to recommend cool zephyr and made ease
1	more easy wholesome thirst and appetite
1	more grateful to their supper fruits they fell 
1	nectarine fruits which the compliant boughs
1	yielded them side long as they sat recline
1	on the soft downy bank damasked with flowers 
1	the savoury pulp they chew and in the rind 
1	still as they thirsted scoop the brimming stream 
1	nor gentle purpose nor endearing smiles
1	wanted nor youthful dalliance as beseems
1	fair couple linked in happy nuptial league 
1	alone as they about them frisking played
1	all beasts of the earth since wild and of all chase
1	in wood or wilderness forest or den 
1	sporting the lion ramped and in his paw
1	dandled the kid bears tigers ounces pards 
1	gambolled before them the unwieldy elephant 
1	to make them mirth used all his might and wreathed
1	his lithe proboscis close the serpent sly 
1	insinuating wove with gordian twine
1	his braided train and of his fatal guile
1	gave proof unheeded others on the grass
1	couched and now filled with pasture gazing sat 
1	or bedward ruminating for the sun 
1	declined was hasting now with prone career
1	to the ocean isles and in the ascending scale
1	of heaven the stars that usher evening rose 
1	when satan still in gaze as first he stood 
1	scarce thus at length failed speech recovered sad 
1	o hell what do mine eyes with grief behold 
1	into our room of bliss thus high advanced
1	creatures of other mould earth born perhaps 
1	not spirits yet to heavenly spirits bright
1	little inferiour whom my thoughts pursue
1	with wonder and could love so lively shines
1	in them divine resemblance and such grace
1	the hand that formed them on their shape hath poured 
1	ah gentle pair ye little think how nigh
1	your change approaches when all these delights
1	will vanish and deliver ye to woe 
1	more woe the more your taste is now of joy 
1	happy but for so happy ill secured
1	long to continue and this high seat your heaven
1	ill fenced for heaven to keep out such a foe
1	as now is entered yet no purposed foe
1	to you whom i could pity thus forlorn 
1	though i unpitied league with you i seek 
1	and mutual amity so strait so close 
1	that i with you must dwell or you with me
1	henceforth my dwelling haply may not please 
1	like this fair paradise your sense yet such
1	accept your maker s work he gave it me 
1	which i as freely give hell shall unfold 
1	to entertain you two her widest gates 
1	and send forth all her kings there will be room 
1	not like these narrow limits to receive
1	your numerous offspring if no better place 
1	thank him who puts me loth to this revenge
1	on you who wrong me not for him who wronged 
1	and should i at your harmless innocence
1	melt as i do yet publick reason just 
1	honour and empire with revenge enlarged 
1	by conquering this new world compels me now
1	to do what else though damned i should abhor 
1	so spake the fiend and with necessity 
1	the tyrant s plea excused his devilish deeds 
1	then from his lofty stand on that high tree
1	down he alights among the sportful herd
1	of those four footed kinds himself now one 
1	now other as their shape served best his end
1	nearer to view his prey and unespied 
1	to mark what of their state he more might learn 
1	by word or action marked about them round
1	a lion now he stalks with fiery glare 
1	then as a tiger who by chance hath spied
1	in some purlieu two gentle fawns at play 
1	straight couches close then rising changes oft
1	his couchant watch as one who chose his ground 
1	whence rushing he might surest seize them both 
1	griped in each paw when adam first of men
1	to first of women eve thus moving speech 
1	turned him all ear to hear new utterance flow 
1	sole partner and sole part of all these joys 
1	dearer thyself than all needs must the power
1	that made us and for us this ample world 
1	be infinitely good and of his good
1	as liberal and free as infinite 
1	that raised us from the dust and placed us here
1	in all this happiness who at his hand
1	have nothing merited nor can perform
1	aught whereof he hath need he who requires
1	from us no other service than to keep
1	this one this easy charge of all the trees
1	in paradise that bear delicious fruit
1	so various not to taste that only tree
1	of knowledge planted by the tree of life 
1	so near grows death to life whate er death is 
1	some dreadful thing no doubt for well thou knowest
1	god hath pronounced it death to taste that tree 
1	the only sign of our obedience left 
1	among so many signs of power and rule
1	conferred upon us and dominion given
1	over all other creatures that possess
1	earth air and sea then let us not think hard
1	one easy prohibition who enjoy
1	free leave so large to all things else and choice
1	unlimited of manifold delights 
1	but let us ever praise him and extol
1	his bounty following our delightful task 
1	to prune these growing plants and tend these flowers 
1	which were it toilsome yet with thee were sweet 
1	to whom thus eve replied o thou for whom
1	and from whom i was formed flesh of thy flesh 
1	and without whom am to no end my guide
1	and head what thou hast said is just and right 
1	for we to him indeed all praises owe 
1	and daily thanks i chiefly who enjoy
1	so far the happier lot enjoying thee
1	pre eminent by so much odds while thou
1	like consort to thyself canst no where find 
1	that day i oft remember when from sleep
1	i first awaked and found myself reposed
1	under a shade on flowers much wondering where
1	and what i was whence thither brought and how 
1	not distant far from thence a murmuring sound
1	of waters issued from a cave and spread
1	into a liquid plain then stood unmoved
1	pure as the expanse of heaven i thither went
1	with unexperienced thought and laid me down
1	on the green bank to look into the clear
1	smooth lake that to me seemed another sky 
1	as i bent down to look just opposite
1	a shape within the watery gleam appeared 
1	bending to look on me i started back 
1	it started back but pleased i soon returned 
1	pleased it returned as soon with answering looks
1	of sympathy and love there i had fixed
1	mine eyes till now and pined with vain desire 
1	had not a voice thus warned me what thou seest 
1	what there thou seest fair creature is thyself 
1	with thee it came and goes but follow me 
1	and i will bring thee where no shadow stays
1	thy coming and thy soft embraces he
1	whose image thou art him thou shalt enjoy
1	inseparably thine to him shalt bear
1	multitudes like thyself and thence be called
1	mother of human race what could i do 
1	but follow straight invisibly thus led 
1	till i espied thee fair indeed and tall 
1	under a platane yet methought less fair 
1	less winning soft less amiably mild 
1	than that smooth watery image back i turned 
1	thou following cryedst aloud return fair eve 
1	whom flyest thou whom thou flyest of him thou art 
1	his flesh his bone to give thee being i lent
1	out of my side to thee nearest my heart 
1	substantial life to have thee by my side
1	henceforth an individual solace dear 
1	part of my soul i seek thee and thee claim
1	my other half with that thy gentle hand
1	seised mine i yielded and from that time see
1	how beauty is excelled by manly grace 
1	and wisdom which alone is truly fair 
1	so spake our general mother and with eyes
1	of conjugal attraction unreproved 
1	and meek surrender half embracing leaned
1	on our first father half her swelling breast
1	naked met his under the flowing gold
1	of her loose tresses hid he in delight
1	both of her beauty and submissive charms 
1	smiled with superiour love as jupiter
1	on juno smiles when he impregns the clouds
1	that shed mayflowers and pressed her matron lip
1	with kisses pure aside the devil turned
1	for envy yet with jealous leer malign
1	eyed them askance and to himself thus plained 
1	sight hateful sight tormenting thus these two 
1	imparadised in one another s arms 
1	the happier eden shall enjoy their fill
1	of bliss on bliss while i to hell am thrust 
1	where neither joy nor love but fierce desire 
1	among our other torments not the least 
1	still unfulfilled with pain of longing pines 
1	yet let me not forget what i have gained
1	from their own mouths all is not theirs it seems 
1	one fatal tree there stands of knowledge called 
1	forbidden them to taste knowledge forbidden
1	suspicious reasonless why should their lord
1	envy them that can it be sin to know 
1	can it be death and do they only stand
1	by ignorance is that their happy state 
1	the proof of their obedience and their faith 
1	o fair foundation laid whereon to build
1	their ruin hence i will excite their minds
1	with more desire to know and to reject
1	envious commands invented with design
1	to keep them low whom knowledge might exalt
1	equal with gods aspiring to be such 
1	they taste and die what likelier can ensue
1	but first with narrow search i must walk round
1	this garden and no corner leave unspied 
1	a chance but chance may lead where i may meet
1	some wandering spirit of heaven by fountain side 
1	or in thick shade retired from him to draw
1	what further would be learned live while ye may 
1	yet happy pair enjoy till i return 
1	short pleasures for long woes are to succeed 
1	so saying his proud step he scornful turned 
1	but with sly circumspection and began
1	through wood through waste o er hill o er dale his roam
1	mean while in utmost longitude where heaven
1	with earth and ocean meets the setting sun
1	slowly descended and with right aspect
1	against the eastern gate of paradise
1	levelled his evening rays it was a rock
1	of alabaster piled up to the clouds 
1	conspicuous far winding with one ascent
1	accessible from earth one entrance high 
1	the rest was craggy cliff that overhung
1	still as it rose impossible to climb 
1	betwixt these rocky pillars gabriel sat 
1	chief of the angelick guards awaiting night 
1	about him exercised heroick games
1	the unarmed youth of heaven but nigh at hand
1	celestial armoury shields helms and spears 
1	hung high with diamond flaming and with gold 
1	thither came uriel gliding through the even
1	on a sun beam swift as a shooting star
1	in autumn thwarts the night when vapours fired
1	impress the air and shows the mariner
1	from what point of his compass to beware
1	impetuous winds he thus began in haste 
1	gabriel to thee thy course by lot hath given
1	charge and strict watch that to this happy place
1	no evil thing approach or enter in 
1	this day at highth of noon came to my sphere
1	a spirit zealous as he seemed to know
1	more of the almighty s works and chiefly man 
1	god s latest image i described his way
1	bent all on speed and marked his aery gait 
1	but in the mount that lies from eden north 
1	where he first lighted soon discerned his looks
1	alien from heaven with passions foul obscured 
1	mine eye pursued him still but under shade
1	lost sight of him one of the banished crew 
1	i fear hath ventured from the deep to raise
1	new troubles him thy care must be to find 
1	to whom the winged warriour thus returned 
1	uriel no wonder if thy perfect sight 
1	amid the sun s bright circle where thou sitst 
1	see far and wide in at this gate none pass
1	the vigilance here placed but such as come
1	well known from heaven and since meridian hour
1	no creature thence if spirit of other sort 
1	so minded have o er leaped these earthly bounds
1	on purpose hard thou knowest it to exclude
1	spiritual substance with corporeal bar 
1	but if within the circuit of these walks 
1	in whatsoever shape he lurk of whom
1	thou tellest by morrow dawning i shall know 
1	so promised he and uriel to his charge
1	returned on that bright beam whose point now raised
1	bore him slope downward to the sun now fallen
1	beneath the azores whether the prime orb 
1	incredible how swift had thither rolled
1	diurnal or this less volubil earth 
1	by shorter flight to the east had left him there
1	arraying with reflected purple and gold
1	the clouds that on his western throne attend 
1	now came still evening on and twilight gray
1	had in her sober livery all things clad 
1	silence accompanied for beast and bird 
1	they to their grassy couch these to their nests
1	were slunk all but the wakeful nightingale 
1	she all night long her amorous descant sung 
1	silence was pleased now glowed the firmament
1	with living sapphires hesperus that led
1	the starry host rode brightest till the moon 
1	rising in clouded majesty at length
1	apparent queen unveiled her peerless light 
1	and o er the dark her silver mantle threw 
1	when adam thus to eve fair consort the hour
1	of night and all things now retired to rest 
1	mind us of like repose since god hath set
1	labour and rest as day and night to men
1	successive and the timely dew of sleep 
1	now falling with soft slumbrous weight inclines
1	our eye lids other creatures all day long
1	rove idle unemployed and less need rest 
1	man hath his daily work of body or mind
1	appointed which declares his dignity 
1	and the regard of heaven on all his ways 
1	while other animals unactive range 
1	and of their doings god takes no account 
1	to morrow ere fresh morning streak the east
1	with first approach of light we must be risen 
1	and at our pleasant labour to reform
1	yon flowery arbours yonder alleys green 
1	our walk at noon with branches overgrown 
1	that mock our scant manuring and require
1	more hands than ours to lop their wanton growth 
1	those blossoms also and those dropping gums 
1	that lie bestrown unsightly and unsmooth 
1	ask riddance if we mean to tread with ease 
1	mean while as nature wills night bids us rest 
1	to whom thus eve with perfect beauty adorned
1	my author and disposer what thou bidst
1	unargued i obey so god ordains 
1	god is thy law thou mine to know no more
1	is woman s happiest knowledge and her praise 
1	with thee conversing i forget all time 
1	all seasons and their change all please alike 
1	sweet is the breath of morn her rising sweet 
1	with charm of earliest birds pleasant the sun 
1	when first on this delightful land he spreads
1	his orient beams on herb tree fruit and flower 
1	glistering with dew fragrant the fertile earth
1	after soft showers and sweet the coming on
1	of grateful evening mild then silent night 
1	with this her solemn bird and this fair moon 
1	and these the gems of heaven her starry train 
1	but neither breath of morn when she ascends
1	with charm of earliest birds nor rising sun
1	on this delightful land nor herb fruit flower 
1	glistering with dew nor fragrance after showers 
1	nor grateful evening mild nor silent night 
1	with this her solemn bird nor walk by moon 
1	or glittering star light without thee is sweet 
1	but wherefore all night long shine these for whom
1	this glorious sight when sleep hath shut all eyes 
1	to whom our general ancestor replied 
1	daughter of god and man accomplished eve 
1	these have their course to finish round the earth 
1	by morrow evening and from land to land
1	in order though to nations yet unborn 
1	ministring light prepared they set and rise 
1	lest total darkness should by night regain
1	her old possession and extinguish life
1	in nature and all things which these soft fires
1	not only enlighten but with kindly heat
1	of various influence foment and warm 
1	temper or nourish or in part shed down
1	their stellar virtue on all kinds that grow
1	on earth made hereby apter to receive
1	perfection from the sun s more potent ray 
1	these then though unbeheld in deep of night 
1	shine not in vain nor think though men were none 
1	that heaven would want spectators god want praise 
1	millions of spiritual creatures walk the earth
1	unseen both when we wake and when we sleep 
1	all these with ceaseless praise his works behold
1	both day and night how often from the steep
1	of echoing hill or thicket have we heard
1	celestial voices to the midnight air 
1	sole or responsive each to others note 
1	singing their great creator oft in bands
1	while they keep watch or nightly rounding walk 
1	with heavenly touch of instrumental sounds
1	in full harmonick number joined their songs
1	divide the night and lift our thoughts to heaven 
1	thus talking hand in hand alone they passed
1	on to their blissful bower it was a place
1	chosen by the sovran planter when he framed
1	all things to man s delightful use the roof
1	of thickest covert was inwoven shade
1	laurel and myrtle and what higher grew
1	of firm and fragrant leaf on either side
1	acanthus and each odorous bushy shrub 
1	fenced up the verdant wall each beauteous flower 
1	iris all hues roses and jessamin 
1	reared high their flourished heads between and wrought
1	mosaick underfoot the violet 
1	crocus and hyacinth with rich inlay
1	broidered the ground more coloured than with stone
1	of costliest emblem other creature here 
1	bird beast insect or worm durst enter none 
1	such was their awe of man in shadier bower
1	more sacred and sequestered though but feigned 
1	pan or sylvanus never slept nor nymph
1	nor faunus haunted here in close recess 
1	with flowers garlands and sweet smelling herbs 
1	espoused eve decked first her nuptial bed 
1	and heavenly quires the hymenaean sung 
1	what day the genial angel to our sire
1	brought her in naked beauty more adorned 
1	more lovely than pandora whom the gods
1	endowed with all their gifts and o too like
1	in sad event when to the unwiser son
1	mankind with her fair looks to be avenged
1	on him who had stole jove s authentick fire 
1	thus at their shady lodge arrived both stood 
1	both turned and under open sky adored
1	the god that made both sky air earth and heaven 
1	which they beheld the moon s resplendent globe 
1	and starry pole thou also madest the night 
1	maker omnipotent and thou the day 
1	which we in our appointed work employed 
1	have finished happy in our mutual help
1	and mutual love the crown of all our bliss
1	ordained by thee and this delicious place
1	for us too large where thy abundance wants
1	partakers and uncropt falls to the ground 
1	but thou hast promised from us two a race
1	to fill the earth who shall with us extol
1	thy goodness infinite both when we wake 
1	and when we seek as now thy gift of sleep 
1	this said unanimous and other rites
1	observing none but adoration pure
1	which god likes best into their inmost bower
1	handed they went and eased the putting off
1	these troublesome disguises which we wear 
1	straight side by side were laid nor turned i ween 
1	adam from his fair spouse nor eve the rites
1	mysterious of connubial love refused 
1	whatever hypocrites austerely talk
1	of purity and place and innocence 
1	defaming as impure what god declares
1	pure and commands to some leaves free to all 
1	our maker bids encrease who bids abstain
1	hail wedded love mysterious law true source
1	of human offspring sole propriety
1	in paradise of all things common else 
1	by thee adulterous lust was driven from men
1	among the bestial herds to range by thee
1	founded in reason loyal just and pure 
1	relations dear and all the charities
1	of father son and brother first were known 
1	far be it that i should write thee sin or blame 
1	or think thee unbefitting holiest place 
1	perpetual fountain of domestick sweets 
1	whose bed is undefiled and chaste pronounced 
1	present or past as saints and patriarchs used 
1	here love his golden shafts employs here lights
1	his constant lamp and waves his purple wings 
1	reigns here and revels not in the bought smile
1	of harlots loveless joyless unendeared 
1	casual fruition nor in court amours 
1	mixed dance or wanton mask or midnight ball 
1	or serenate which the starved lover sings
1	to his proud fair best quitted with disdain 
1	these lulled by nightingales embracing slept 
1	and on their naked limbs the flowery roof
1	showered roses which the morn repaired sleep on 
1	blest pair and o yet happiest if ye seek
1	no happier state and know to know no more 
1	now had night measured with her shadowy cone
1	half way up hill this vast sublunar vault 
1	and from their ivory port the cherubim 
1	forth issuing at the accustomed hour stood armed
1	to their night watches in warlike parade 
1	when gabriel to his next in power thus spake 
1	uzziel half these draw off and coast the south
1	with strictest watch these other wheel the north 
1	our circuit meets full west as flame they part 
1	half wheeling to the shield half to the spear 
1	from these two strong and subtle spirits he called
1	that near him stood and gave them thus in charge 
1	ithuriel and zephon with winged speed
1	search through this garden leave unsearched no nook 
1	but chiefly where those two fair creatures lodge 
1	now laid perhaps asleep secure of harm 
1	this evening from the sun s decline arrived 
1	who tells of some infernal spirit seen
1	hitherward bent who could have thought escaped
1	the bars of hell on errand bad no doubt 
1	such where ye find seise fast and hither bring 
1	so saying on he led his radiant files 
1	dazzling the moon these to the bower direct
1	in search of whom they sought him there they found
1	squat like a toad close at the ear of eve 
1	assaying by his devilish art to reach
1	the organs of her fancy and with them forge
1	illusions as he list phantasms and dreams 
1	or if inspiring venom he might taint
1	the animal spirits that from pure blood arise
1	like gentle breaths from rivers pure thence raise
1	at least distempered discontented thoughts 
1	vain hopes vain aims inordinate desires 
1	blown up with high conceits ingendering pride 
1	him thus intent ithuriel with his spear
1	touched lightly for no falshood can endure
1	touch of celestial temper but returns
1	of force to its own likeness up he starts
1	discovered and surprised as when a spark
1	lights on a heap of nitrous powder laid
1	fit for the tun some magazine to store
1	against a rumoured war the smutty grain 
1	with sudden blaze diffused inflames the air 
1	so started up in his own shape the fiend 
1	back stept those two fair angels half amazed
1	so sudden to behold the grisly king 
1	yet thus unmoved with fear accost him soon 
1	which of those rebel spirits adjudged to hell
1	comest thou escaped thy prison and transformed 
1	why sat st thou like an enemy in wait 
1	here watching at the head of these that sleep 
1	know ye not then said satan filled with scorn 
1	know ye not me ye knew me once no mate
1	for you there sitting where ye durst not soar 
1	not to know me argues yourselves unknown 
1	the lowest of your throng or if ye know 
1	why ask ye and superfluous begin
1	your message like to end as much in vain 
1	to whom thus zephon answering scorn with scorn 
1	think not revolted spirit thy shape the same 
1	or undiminished brightness to be known 
1	as when thou stoodest in heaven upright and pure 
1	that glory then when thou no more wast good 
1	departed from thee and thou resemblest now
1	thy sin and place of doom obscure and foul 
1	but come for thou be sure shalt give account
1	to him who sent us whose charge is to keep
1	this place inviolable and these from harm 
1	so spake the cherub and his grave rebuke 
1	severe in youthful beauty added grace
1	invincible abashed the devil stood 
1	and felt how awful goodness is and saw
1	virtue in her shape how lovely saw and pined
1	his loss but chiefly to find here observed
1	his lustre visibly impaired yet seemed
1	undaunted if i must contend said he 
1	best with the best the sender not the sent 
1	or all at once more glory will be won 
1	or less be lost thy fear said zephon bold 
1	will save us trial what the least can do
1	single against thee wicked and thence weak 
1	the fiend replied not overcome with rage 
1	but like a proud steed reined went haughty on 
1	champing his iron curb to strive or fly
1	he held it vain awe from above had quelled
1	his heart not else dismayed now drew they nigh
1	the western point where those half rounding guards
1	just met and closing stood in squadron joined 
1	a waiting next command to whom their chief 
1	gabriel from the front thus called aloud 
1	o friends i hear the tread of nimble feet
1	hasting this way and now by glimpse discern
1	ithuriel and zephon through the shade 
1	and with them comes a third of regal port 
1	but faded splendour wan who by his gait
1	and fierce demeanour seems the prince of hell 
1	not likely to part hence without contest 
1	stand firm for in his look defiance lours 
1	he scarce had ended when those two approached 
1	and brief related whom they brought where found 
1	how busied in what form and posture couched 
1	to whom with stern regard thus gabriel spake 
1	why hast thou satan broke the bounds prescribed
1	to thy transgressions and disturbed the charge
1	of others who approve not to transgress
1	by thy example but have power and right
1	to question thy bold entrance on this place 
1	employed it seems to violate sleep and those
1	whose dwelling god hath planted here in bliss 
1	to whom thus satan with contemptuous brow 
1	gabriel thou hadst in heaven the esteem of wise 
1	and such i held thee but this question asked
1	puts me in doubt lives there who loves his pain 
1	who would not finding way break loose from hell 
1	though thither doomed thou wouldst thyself no doubt
1	and boldly venture to whatever place
1	farthest from pain where thou mightst hope to change
1	torment with ease and soonest recompense
1	dole with delight which in this place i sought 
1	to thee no reason who knowest only good 
1	but evil hast not tried and wilt object
1	his will who bounds us let him surer bar
1	his iron gates if he intends our stay
1	in that dark durance thus much what was asked 
1	the rest is true they found me where they say 
1	but that implies not violence or harm 
1	thus he in scorn the warlike angel moved 
1	disdainfully half smiling thus replied 
1	o loss of one in heaven to judge of wise
1	since satan fell whom folly overthrew 
1	and now returns him from his prison scaped 
1	gravely in doubt whether to hold them wise
1	or not who ask what boldness brought him hither
1	unlicensed from his bounds in hell prescribed 
1	so wise he judges it to fly from pain
1	however and to scape his punishment 
1	so judge thou still presumptuous till the wrath 
1	which thou incurrest by flying meet thy flight
1	sevenfold and scourge that wisdom back to hell 
1	which taught thee yet no better that no pain
1	can equal anger infinite provoked 
1	but wherefore thou alone wherefore with thee
1	came not all hell broke loose or thou than they
1	less hardy to endure courageous chief 
1	the first in flight from pain hadst thou alleged
1	to thy deserted host this cause of flight 
1	thou surely hadst not come sole fugitive 
1	to which the fiend thus answered frowning stern 
1	not that i less endure or shrink from pain 
1	insulting angel well thou knowest i stood
1	thy fiercest when in battle to thy aid
1	the blasting vollied thunder made all speed 
1	and seconded thy else not dreaded spear 
1	but still thy words at random as before 
1	argue thy inexperience what behoves
1	from hard assays and ill successes past
1	a faithful leader not to hazard all
1	through ways of danger by himself untried 
1	i therefore i alone first undertook
1	to wing the desolate abyss and spy
1	this new created world whereof in hell
1	fame is not silent here in hope to find
1	better abode and my afflicted powers
1	to settle here on earth or in mid air 
1	though for possession put to try once more
1	what thou and thy gay legions dare against 
1	whose easier business were to serve their lord
1	high up in heaven with songs to hymn his throne 
1	and practised distances to cringe not fight 
1	to whom the warriour angel soon replied 
1	to say and straight unsay pretending first
1	wise to fly pain professing next the spy 
1	argues no leader but a liar traced 
1	satan and couldst thou faithful add o name 
1	o sacred name of faithfulness profaned 
1	faithful to whom to thy rebellious crew 
1	army of fiends fit body to fit head 
1	was this your discipline and faith engaged 
1	your military obedience to dissolve
1	allegiance to the acknowledged power supreme 
1	and thou sly hypocrite who now wouldst seem
1	patron of liberty who more than thou
1	once fawned and cringed and servilely adored
1	heaven s awful monarch wherefore but in hope
1	to dispossess him and thyself to reign 
1	but mark what i arreed thee now avant 
1	fly neither whence thou fledst if from this hour
1	within these hallowed limits thou appear 
1	back to the infernal pit i drag thee chained 
1	and seal thee so as henceforth not to scorn
1	the facile gates of hell too slightly barred 
1	so threatened he but satan to no threats
1	gave heed but waxing more in rage replied 
1	then when i am thy captive talk of chains 
1	proud limitary cherub but ere then
1	far heavier load thyself expect to feel
1	from my prevailing arm though heaven s king
1	ride on thy wings and thou with thy compeers 
1	us d to the yoke drawest his triumphant wheels
1	in progress through the road of heaven star paved 
1	while thus he spake the angelick squadron bright
1	turned fiery red sharpening in mooned horns
1	their phalanx and began to hem him round
1	with ported spears as thick as when a field
1	of ceres ripe for harvest waving bends
1	her bearded grove of ears which way the wind
1	sways them the careful plowman doubting stands 
1	left on the threshing floor his hopeless sheaves
1	prove chaff on the other side satan alarmed 
1	collecting all his might dilated stood 
1	like teneriff or atlas unremoved 
1	his stature reached the sky and on his crest
1	sat horrour plumed nor wanted in his grasp
1	what seemed both spear and shield now dreadful deeds
1	might have ensued nor only paradise
1	in this commotion but the starry cope
1	of heaven perhaps or all the elements
1	at least had gone to wrack disturbed and torn
1	with violence of this conflict had not soon
1	the eternal to prevent such horrid fray 
1	hung forth in heaven his golden scales yet seen
1	betwixt astrea and the scorpion sign 
1	wherein all things created first he weighed 
1	the pendulous round earth with balanced air
1	in counterpoise now ponders all events 
1	battles and realms in these he put two weights 
1	the sequel each of parting and of fight 
1	the latter quick up flew and kicked the beam 
1	which gabriel spying thus bespake the fiend 
1	satan i know thy strength and thou knowest mine 
1	neither our own but given what folly then
1	to boast what arms can do since thine no more
1	than heaven permits nor mine though doubled now
1	to trample thee as mire for proof look up 
1	and read thy lot in yon celestial sign 
1	where thou art weighed and shown how light how weak 
1	if thou resist the fiend looked up and knew
1	his mounted scale aloft nor more but fled
1	murmuring and with him fled the shades of night 
1	now morn her rosy steps in the eastern clime
1	advancing sowed the earth with orient pearl 
1	when adam waked so customed for his sleep
1	was aery light from pure digestion bred 
1	and temperate vapours bland which the only sound
1	of leaves and fuming rills aurora s fan 
1	lightly dispersed and the shrill matin song
1	of birds on every bough so much the more
1	his wonder was to find unwakened eve
1	with tresses discomposed and glowing cheek 
1	as through unquiet rest he on his side
1	leaning half raised with looks of cordial love
1	hung over her enamoured and beheld
1	beauty which whether waking or asleep 
1	shot forth peculiar graces then with voice
1	mild as when zephyrus on flora breathes 
1	her hand soft touching whispered thus awake 
1	my fairest my espoused my latest found 
1	heaven s last best gift my ever new delight 
1	awake the morning shines and the fresh field
1	calls us we lose the prime to mark how spring
1	our tender plants how blows the citron grove 
1	what drops the myrrh and what the balmy reed 
1	how nature paints her colours how the bee
1	sits on the bloom extracting liquid sweet 
1	such whispering waked her but with startled eye
1	on adam whom embracing thus she spake 
1	o sole in whom my thoughts find all repose 
1	my glory my perfection glad i see
1	thy face and morn returned for i this night
1	 such night till this i never passed have dreamed 
1	if dreamed not as i oft am wont of thee 
1	works of day past or morrow s next design 
1	but of offence and trouble which my mind
1	knew never till this irksome night methought 
1	close at mine ear one called me forth to walk
1	with gentle voice i thought it thine it said 
1	 why sleepest thou eve now is the pleasant time 
1	the cool the silent save where silence yields
1	to the night warbling bird that now awake
1	tunes sweetest his love laboured song now reigns
1	full orbed the moon and with more pleasing light
1	shadowy sets off the face of things in vain 
1	if none regard heaven wakes with all his eyes 
1	whom to behold but thee nature s desire 
1	in whose sight all things joy with ravishment
1	attracted by thy beauty still to gaze 
1	i rose as at thy call but found thee not 
1	to find thee i directed then my walk 
1	and on methought alone i passed through ways
1	that brought me on a sudden to the tree
1	of interdicted knowledge fair it seemed 
1	much fairer to my fancy than by day 
1	and as i wondering looked beside it stood
1	one shaped and winged like one of those from heaven
1	by us oft seen his dewy locks distilled
1	ambrosia on that tree he also gazed 
1	and o fair plant said he with fruit surcharged 
1	deigns none to ease thy load and taste thy sweet 
1	nor god nor man is knowledge so despised 
1	or envy or what reserve forbids to taste 
1	forbid who will none shall from me withhold
1	longer thy offered good why else set here 
1	this said he paused not but with venturous arm
1	he plucked he tasted me damp horrour chilled
1	at such bold words vouched with a deed so bold 
1	but he thus overjoyed o fruit divine 
1	sweet of thyself but much more sweet thus cropt 
1	forbidden here it seems as only fit
1	for gods yet able to make gods of men 
1	and why not gods of men since good the more
1	communicated more abundant grows 
1	the author not impaired but honoured more 
1	here happy creature fair angelick eve 
1	partake thou also happy though thou art 
1	happier thou mayest be worthier canst not be 
1	taste this and be henceforth among the gods
1	thyself a goddess not to earth confined 
1	but sometimes in the air as we sometimes
1	ascend to heaven by merit thine and see
1	what life the gods live there and such live thou 
1	so saying he drew nigh and to me held 
1	even to my mouth of that same fruit held part
1	which he had plucked the pleasant savoury smell
1	so quickened appetite that i methought 
1	could not but taste forthwith up to the clouds
1	with him i flew and underneath beheld
1	the earth outstretched immense a prospect wide
1	and various wondering at my flight and change
1	to this high exaltation suddenly
1	my guide was gone and i methought sunk down 
1	and fell asleep but o how glad i waked
1	to find this but a dream thus eve her night
1	related and thus adam answered sad 
1	best image of myself and dearer half 
1	the trouble of thy thoughts this night in sleep
1	affects me equally nor can i like
1	this uncouth dream of evil sprung i fear 
1	yet evil whence in thee can harbour none 
1	created pure but know that in the soul
1	are many lesser faculties that serve
1	reason as chief among these fancy next
1	her office holds of all external things
1	which the five watchful senses represent 
1	she forms imaginations aery shapes 
1	which reason joining or disjoining frames
1	all what we affirm or what deny and call
1	our knowledge or opinion then retires
1	into her private cell when nature rests 
1	oft in her absence mimick fancy wakes
1	to imitate her but misjoining shapes 
1	wild work produces oft and most in dreams 
1	ill matching words and deeds long past or late 
1	some such resemblances methinks i find
1	of our last evening s talk in this thy dream 
1	but with addition strange yet be not sad 
1	evil into the mind of god or man
1	may come and go so unreproved and leave
1	no spot or blame behind which gives me hope
1	that what in sleep thou didst abhor to dream 
1	waking thou never will consent to do 
1	be not disheartened then nor cloud those looks 
1	that wont to be more cheerful and serene 
1	than when fair morning first smiles on the world 
1	and let us to our fresh employments rise
1	among the groves the fountains and the flowers
1	that open now their choisest bosomed smells 
1	reserved from night and kept for thee in store 
1	so cheered he his fair spouse and she was cheered 
1	but silently a gentle tear let fall
1	from either eye and wiped them with her hair 
1	two other precious drops that ready stood 
1	each in their crystal sluice he ere they fell
1	kissed as the gracious signs of sweet remorse
1	and pious awe that feared to have offended 
1	so all was cleared and to the field they haste 
1	but first from under shady arborous roof
1	soon as they forth were come to open sight
1	of day spring and the sun who scarce up risen 
1	with wheels yet hovering o er the ocean brim 
1	shot parallel to the earth his dewy ray 
1	discovering in wide landskip all the east
1	of paradise and eden s happy plains 
1	lowly they bowed adoring and began
1	their orisons each morning duly paid
1	in various style for neither various style
1	nor holy rapture wanted they to praise
1	their maker in fit strains pronounced or sung
1	unmeditated such prompt eloquence
1	flowed from their lips in prose or numerous verse 
1	more tuneable than needed lute or harp
1	to add more sweetness and they thus began 
1	these are thy glorious works parent of good 
1	almighty thine this universal frame 
1	thus wonderous fair thyself how wonderous then 
1	unspeakable who sitst above these heavens
1	to us invisible or dimly seen
1	in these thy lowest works yet these declare
1	thy goodness beyond thought and power divine 
1	speak ye who best can tell ye sons of light 
1	angels for ye behold him and with songs
1	and choral symphonies day without night 
1	circle his throne rejoicing ye in heaven
1	on earth join all ye creatures to extol
1	him first him last him midst and without end 
1	fairest of stars last in the train of night 
1	if better thou belong not to the dawn 
1	sure pledge of day that crownest the smiling morn
1	with thy bright circlet praise him in thy sphere 
1	while day arises that sweet hour of prime 
1	thou sun of this great world both eye and soul 
1	acknowledge him thy greater sound his praise
1	in thy eternal course both when thou climbest 
1	and when high noon hast gained and when thou fallest 
1	moon that now meetest the orient sun now flyest 
1	with the fixed stars fixed in their orb that flies 
1	and ye five other wandering fires that move
1	in mystick dance not without song resound
1	his praise who out of darkness called up light 
1	air and ye elements the eldest birth
1	of nature s womb that in quaternion run
1	perpetual circle multiform and mix
1	and nourish all things let your ceaseless change
1	vary to our great maker still new praise 
1	ye mists and exhalations that now rise
1	from hill or steaming lake dusky or gray 
1	till the sun paint your fleecy skirts with gold 
1	in honour to the world s great author rise 
1	whether to deck with clouds the uncoloured sky 
1	or wet the thirsty earth with falling showers 
1	rising or falling still advance his praise 
1	his praise ye winds that from four quarters blow 
1	breathe soft or loud and wave your tops ye pines 
1	with every plant in sign of worship wave 
1	fountains and ye that warble as ye flow 
1	melodious murmurs warbling tune his praise 
1	join voices all ye living souls ye birds 
1	that singing up to heaven gate ascend 
1	bear on your wings and in your notes his praise 
1	ye that in waters glide and ye that walk
1	the earth and stately tread or lowly creep 
1	witness if i be silent morn or even 
1	to hill or valley fountain or fresh shade 
1	made vocal by my song and taught his praise 
1	hail universal lord be bounteous still
1	to give us only good and if the night
1	have gathered aught of evil or concealed 
1	disperse it as now light dispels the dark 
1	so prayed they innocent and to their thoughts
1	firm peace recovered soon and wonted calm 
1	on to their morning s rural work they haste 
1	among sweet dews and flowers where any row
1	of fruit trees over woody reached too far
1	their pampered boughs and needed hands to check
1	fruitless embraces or they led the vine
1	to wed her elm she spoused about him twines
1	her marriageable arms and with him brings
1	her dower the adopted clusters to adorn
1	his barren leaves them thus employed beheld
1	with pity heaven s high king and to him called
1	raphael the sociable spirit that deigned
1	to travel with tobias and secured
1	his marriage with the seventimes wedded maid 
1	raphael said he thou hearest what stir on earth
1	satan from hell scaped through the darksome gulf 
1	hath raised in paradise and how disturbed
1	this night the human pair how he designs
1	in them at once to ruin all mankind 
1	go therefore half this day as friend with friend
1	converse with adam in what bower or shade
1	thou findest him from the heat of noon retired 
1	to respite his day labour with repast 
1	or with repose and such discourse bring on 
1	as may advise him of his happy state 
1	happiness in his power left free to will 
1	left to his own free will his will though free 
1	yet mutable whence warn him to beware
1	he swerve not too secure tell him withal
1	his danger and from whom what enemy 
1	late fallen himself from heaven is plotting now
1	the fall of others from like state of bliss 
1	by violence no for that shall be withstood 
1	but by deceit and lies this let him know 
1	lest wilfully transgressing he pretend
1	surprisal unadmonished unforewarned 
1	so spake the eternal father and fulfilled
1	all justice nor delayed the winged saint
1	after his charge received but from among
1	thousand celestial ardours where he stood
1	veiled with his gorgeous wings up springing light 
1	flew through the midst of heaven the angelick quires 
1	on each hand parting to his speed gave way
1	through all the empyreal road till at the gate
1	of heaven arrived the gate self opened wide
1	on golden hinges turning as by work
1	divine the sovran architect had framed 
1	from hence no cloud or to obstruct his sight 
1	star interposed however small he sees 
1	not unconformed to other shining globes 
1	earth and the garden of god with cedars crowned
1	above all hills as when by night the glass
1	of galileo less assured observes
1	imagined lands and regions in the moon 
1	or pilot from amidst the cyclades
1	delos or samos first appearing kens
1	a cloudy spot down thither prone in flight
1	he speeds and through the vast ethereal sky
1	sails between worlds and worlds with steady wing
1	now on the polar winds then with quick fan
1	winnows the buxom air till within soar
1	of towering eagles to all the fowls he seems
1	a phoenix gazed by all as that sole bird 
1	when to enshrine his reliques in the sun s
1	at once on the eastern cliff of paradise
1	he lights and to his proper shape returns
1	a seraph winged six wings he wore to shade
1	his lineaments divine the pair that clad
1	each shoulder broad came mantling o er his breast
1	with regal ornament the middle pair
