1	soon as midnight brought on the dusky hour
1	friendliest to sleep and silence he resolved
1	with all his legions to dislodge and leave
1	unworshipt unobeyed the throne supreme 
1	contemptuous and his next subordinate
1	awakening thus to him in secret spake 
1	sleepest thou companion dear what sleep can close
1	thy eye lids and rememberest what decree
1	of yesterday so late hath passed the lips
1	of heaven s almighty thou to me thy thoughts
1	wast wont i mine to thee was wont to impart 
1	both waking we were one how then can now
1	thy sleep dissent new laws thou seest imposed 
1	new laws from him who reigns new minds may raise
1	in us who serve new counsels to debate
1	what doubtful may ensue more in this place
1	to utter is not safe assemble thou
1	of all those myriads which we lead the chief 
1	tell them that by command ere yet dim night
1	her shadowy cloud withdraws i am to haste 
1	and all who under me their banners wave 
1	homeward with flying march where we possess
1	the quarters of the north there to prepare
1	fit entertainment to receive our king 
1	the great messiah and his new commands 
1	who speedily through all the hierarchies
1	intends to pass triumphant and give laws 
1	so spake the false arch angel and infused
1	bad influence into the unwary breast
1	of his associate he together calls 
1	or several one by one the regent powers 
1	under him regent tells as he was taught 
1	that the most high commanding now ere night 
1	now ere dim night had disincumbered heaven 
1	the great hierarchal standard was to move 
1	tells the suggested cause and casts between
1	ambiguous words and jealousies to sound
1	or taint integrity but all obeyed
1	the wonted signal and superiour voice
1	of their great potentate for great indeed
1	his name and high was his degree in heaven 
1	his countenance as the morning star that guides
1	the starry flock allured them and with lies
1	drew after him the third part of heaven s host 
1	mean while the eternal eye whose sight discerns
1	abstrusest thoughts from forth his holy mount 
1	and from within the golden lamps that burn
1	nightly before him saw without their light
1	rebellion rising saw in whom how spread
1	among the sons of morn what multitudes
1	were banded to oppose his high decree 
1	and smiling to his only son thus said 
1	son thou in whom my glory i behold
1	in full resplendence heir of all my might 
1	nearly it now concerns us to be sure
1	of our omnipotence and with what arms
1	we mean to hold what anciently we claim
1	of deity or empire such a foe
1	is rising who intends to erect his throne
1	equal to ours throughout the spacious north 
1	nor so content hath in his thought to try
1	in battle what our power is or our right 
1	let us advise and to this hazard draw
1	with speed what force is left and all employ
1	in our defence lest unawares we lose
1	this our high place our sanctuary our hill 
1	to whom the son with calm aspect and clear 
1	lightning divine ineffable serene 
1	made answer mighty father thou thy foes
1	justly hast in derision and secure 
1	laughest at their vain designs and tumults vain 
1	matter to me of glory whom their hate
1	illustrates when they see all regal power
1	given me to quell their pride and in event
1	know whether i be dextrous to subdue
1	thy rebels or be found the worst in heaven 
1	so spake the son but satan with his powers 
1	far was advanced on winged speed an host
1	innumerable as the stars of night 
1	or stars of morning dew drops which the sun
1	impearls on every leaf and every flower 
1	regions they passed the mighty regencies
1	in their triple degrees regions to which
1	all thy dominion adam is no more
1	than what this garden is to all the earth 
1	and all the sea from one entire globose
1	stretched into longitude which having passed 
1	at length into the limits of the north
1	they came and satan to his royal seat
1	high on a hill far blazing as a mount
1	raised on a mount with pyramids and towers
1	from diamond quarries hewn and rocks of gold 
1	the palace of great lucifer so call
1	that structure in the dialect of men
1	interpreted which not long after he
1	affecting all equality with god 
1	in imitation of that mount whereon
1	messiah was declared in sight of heaven 
1	the mountain of the congregation called 
1	for thither he assembled all his train 
1	pretending so commanded to consult
1	about the great reception of their king 
1	thither to come and with calumnious art
1	of counterfeited truth thus held their ears 
1	if these magnifick titles yet remain
1	not merely titular since by decree
1	another now hath to himself engrossed
1	all power and us eclipsed under the name
1	of king anointed for whom all this haste
1	of midnight march and hurried meeting here 
1	this only to consult how we may best 
1	with what may be devised of honours new 
1	receive him coming to receive from us
1	knee tribute yet unpaid prostration vile 
1	too much to one but double how endured 
1	to one and to his image now proclaimed 
1	but what if better counsels might erect
1	our minds and teach us to cast off this yoke 
1	will ye submit your necks and choose to bend
1	the supple knee ye will not if i trust
1	to know ye right or if ye know yourselves
1	natives and sons of heaven possessed before
1	by none and if not equal all yet free 
1	equally free for orders and degrees
1	jar not with liberty but well consist 
1	who can in reason then or right assume
1	monarchy over such as live by right
1	his equals if in power and splendour less 
1	in freedom equal or can introduce
1	law and edict on us who without law
1	err not much less for this to be our lord 
1	and look for adoration to the abuse
1	of those imperial titles which assert
1	our being ordained to govern not to serve 
1	thus far his bold discourse without controul
1	had audience when among the seraphim
1	abdiel than whom none with more zeal adored
1	the deity and divine commands obeyed 
1	stood up and in a flame of zeal severe
1	the current of his fury thus opposed 
1	o argument blasphemous false and proud 
1	words which no ear ever to hear in heaven
1	expected least of all from thee ingrate 
1	in place thyself so high above thy peers 
1	canst thou with impious obloquy condemn
1	the just decree of god pronounced and sworn 
1	that to his only son by right endued
1	with regal scepter every soul in heaven
1	shall bend the knee and in that honour due
1	confess him rightful king unjust thou sayest 
1	flatly unjust to bind with laws the free 
1	and equal over equals to let reign 
1	one over all with unsucceeded power 
1	shalt thou give law to god shalt thou dispute
1	with him the points of liberty who made
1	thee what thou art and formed the powers of heaven
1	such as he pleased and circumscribed their being 
1	yet by experience taught we know how good 
1	and of our good and of our dignity
1	how provident he is how far from thought
1	to make us less bent rather to exalt
1	our happy state under one head more near
1	united but to grant it thee unjust 
1	that equal over equals monarch reign 
1	thyself though great and glorious dost thou count 
1	or all angelick nature joined in one 
1	equal to him begotten son by whom 
1	as by his word the mighty father made
1	all things even thee and all the spirits of heaven
1	by him created in their bright degrees 
1	crowned them with glory and to their glory named
1	essential powers nor by his reign obscured 
1	but more illustrious made since he the head
1	one of our number thus reduced becomes 
1	his laws our laws all honour to him done
1	returns our own cease then this impious rage 
1	and tempt not these but hasten to appease
1	the incensed father and the incensed son 
1	while pardon may be found in time besought 
1	so spake the fervent angel but his zeal
1	none seconded as out of season judged 
1	or singular and rash whereat rejoiced
1	the apostate and more haughty thus replied 
1	that we were formed then sayest thou and the work
1	of secondary hands by task transferred
1	from father to his son strange point and new 
1	doctrine which we would know whence learned who saw
1	when this creation was rememberest thou
1	thy making while the maker gave thee being 
1	we know no time when we were not as now 
1	know none before us self begot self raised
1	by our own quickening power when fatal course
1	had circled his full orb the birth mature
1	of this our native heaven ethereal sons 
1	our puissance is our own our own right hand
1	shall teach us highest deeds by proof to try
1	who is our equal then thou shalt behold
1	whether by supplication we intend
1	address and to begirt the almighty throne
1	beseeching or besieging this report 
1	these tidings carry to the anointed king 
1	and fly ere evil intercept thy flight 
