1	if earth industrious of herself fetch day
1	travelling east and with her part averse
1	from the sun s beam meet night her other part
1	still luminous by his ray what if that light 
1	sent from her through the wide transpicuous air 
1	to the terrestrial moon be as a star 
1	enlightening her by day as she by night
1	this earth reciprocal if land be there 
1	fields and inhabitants her spots thou seest
1	as clouds and clouds may rain and rain produce
1	fruits in her softened soil for some to eat
1	allotted there and other suns perhaps 
1	with their attendant moons thou wilt descry 
1	communicating male and female light 
1	which two great sexes animate the world 
1	stored in each orb perhaps with some that live 
1	for such vast room in nature unpossessed
1	by living soul desart and desolate 
1	only to shine yet scarce to contribute
1	each orb a glimpse of light conveyed so far
1	down to this habitable which returns
1	light back to them is obvious to dispute 
1	but whether thus these things or whether not 
1	but whether the sun predominant in heaven 
1	rise on the earth or earth rise on the sun 
1	he from the east his flaming road begin 
1	or she from west her silent course advance 
1	with inoffensive pace that spinning sleeps
1	on her soft axle while she paces even 
1	and bears thee soft with the smooth hair along 
1	sollicit not thy thoughts with matters hid 
1	leave them to god above him serve and fear 
1	of other creatures as him pleases best 
1	wherever placed let him dispose joy thou
1	in what he gives to thee this paradise
1	and thy fair eve heaven is for thee too high
1	to know what passes there be lowly wise 
1	think only what concerns thee and thy being 
1	dream not of other worlds what creatures there
1	live in what state condition or degree 
1	contented that thus far hath been revealed
1	not of earth only but of highest heaven 
1	to whom thus adam cleared of doubt replied 
1	how fully hast thou satisfied me pure
1	intelligence of heaven angel serene 
1	and freed from intricacies taught to live
1	the easiest way nor with perplexing thoughts
1	to interrupt the sweet of life from which
1	god hath bid dwell far off all anxious cares 
1	and not molest us unless we ourselves
1	seek them with wandering thoughts and notions vain 
1	but apt the mind or fancy is to rove
1	unchecked and of her roving is no end 
1	till warned or by experience taught she learn 
1	that not to know at large of things remote
1	from use obscure and subtle but to know
1	that which before us lies in daily life 
1	is the prime wisdom what is more is fume 
1	or emptiness or fond impertinence 
1	and renders us in things that most concern 
1	unpractised unprepared and still to seek 
1	therefore from this high pitch let us descend
1	a lower flight and speak of things at hand
1	useful whence haply mention may arise
1	of something not unseasonable to ask 
1	by sufferance and thy wonted favour deigned 
1	thee i have heard relating what was done
1	ere my remembrance now hear me relate
1	my story which perhaps thou hast not heard 
1	and day is not yet spent till then thou seest
1	how subtly to detain thee i devise 
1	inviting thee to hear while i relate 
1	fond were it not in hope of thy reply 
1	for while i sit with thee i seem in heaven 
1	and sweeter thy discourse is to my ear
1	than fruits of palm tree pleasantest to thirst
1	and hunger both from labour at the hour
1	of sweet repast they satiate and soon fill 
1	though pleasant but thy words with grace divine
1	imbued bring to their sweetness no satiety 
1	to whom thus raphael answered heavenly meek 
1	nor are thy lips ungraceful sire of men 
1	nor tongue ineloquent for god on thee
1	abundantly his gifts hath also poured
1	inward and outward both his image fair 
1	speaking or mute all comeliness and grace
1	attends thee and each word each motion forms 
1	nor less think we in heaven of thee on earth
1	than of our fellow servant and inquire
1	gladly into the ways of god with man 
1	for god we see hath honoured thee and set
1	on man his equal love say therefore on 
1	for i that day was absent as befel 
1	bound on a voyage uncouth and obscure 
1	far on excursion toward the gates of hell 
1	squared in full legion such command we had 
1	to see that none thence issued forth a spy 
1	or enemy while god was in his work 
1	lest he incensed at such eruption bold 
1	destruction with creation might have mixed 
1	not that they durst without his leave attempt 
1	but us he sends upon his high behests
1	for state as sovran king and to inure
1	our prompt obedience fast we found fast shut 
1	the dismal gates and barricadoed strong 
1	but long ere our approaching heard within
1	noise other than the sound of dance or song 
1	torment and loud lament and furious rage 
1	glad we returned up to the coasts of light
1	ere sabbath evening so we had in charge 
1	but thy relation now for i attend 
1	pleased with thy words no less than thou with mine 
1	so spake the godlike power and thus our sire 
1	for man to tell how human life began
1	is hard for who himself beginning knew
1	desire with thee still longer to converse
1	induced me as new waked from soundest sleep 
1	soft on the flowery herb i found me laid 
1	in balmy sweat which with his beams the sun
1	soon dried and on the reeking moisture fed 
1	straight toward heaven my wondering eyes i turned 
1	and gazed a while the ample sky till raised
1	by quick instinctive motion up i sprung 
1	as thitherward endeavouring and upright
1	stood on my feet about me round i saw
1	hill dale and shady woods and sunny plains 
1	and liquid lapse of murmuring streams by these 
1	creatures that lived and moved and walked or flew 
1	birds on the branches warbling all things smiled 
1	with fragrance and with joy my heart o erflowed 
1	myself i then perused and limb by limb
1	surveyed and sometimes went and sometimes ran
1	with supple joints as lively vigour led 
1	but who i was or where or from what cause 
1	knew not to speak i tried and forthwith spake 
1	my tongue obeyed and readily could name
1	whate er i saw thou sun said i fair light 
1	and thou enlightened earth so fresh and gay 
1	and ye that live and move fair creatures tell 
1	tell if ye saw how i came thus how here 
1	not of myself by some great maker then 
1	in goodness and in power pre eminent 
1	tell me how may i know him how adore 
1	from whom i have that thus i move and live 
1	and feel that i am happier than i know 
1	while thus i called and strayed i knew not whither 
1	from where i first drew air and first beheld
1	this happy light when answer none returned 
1	on a green shady bank profuse of flowers 
1	pensive i sat me down there gentle sleep
1	first found me and with soft oppression seised
1	my droused sense untroubled though i thought
1	i then was passing to my former state
1	insensible and forthwith to dissolve 
1	when suddenly stood at my head a dream 
1	whose inward apparition gently moved
1	my fancy to believe i yet had being 
1	and lived one came methought of shape divine 
1	and said thy mansion wants thee adam rise 
1	first man of men innumerable ordained
1	first father called by thee i come thy guide
1	to the garden of bliss thy seat prepared 
1	so saying by the hand he took me raised 
1	and over fields and waters as in air
1	smooth sliding without step last led me up
1	a woody mountain whose high top was plain 
1	a circuit wide enclosed with goodliest trees
1	planted with walks and bowers that what i saw
1	of earth before scarce pleasant seemed each tree 
1	loaden with fairest fruit that hung to the eye
1	tempting stirred in me sudden appetite
1	to pluck and eat whereat i waked and found
1	before mine eyes all real as the dream
1	had lively shadowed here had new begun
1	my wandering had not he who was my guide
1	up hither from among the trees appeared 
1	presence divine rejoicing but with awe 
1	in adoration at his feet i fell
1	submiss he reared me and whom thou soughtest i am 
1	said mildly author of all this thou seest
1	above or round about thee or beneath 
1	this paradise i give thee count it thine
1	to till and keep and of the fruit to eat 
1	of every tree that in the garden grows
1	eat freely with glad heart fear here no dearth 
1	but of the tree whose operation brings
1	knowledge of good and ill which i have set
1	the pledge of thy obedience and thy faith 
1	amid the garden by the tree of life 
1	remember what i warn thee shun to taste 
1	and shun the bitter consequence for know 
1	the day thou eatest thereof my sole command
1	transgressed inevitably thou shalt die 
1	from that day mortal and this happy state
1	shalt lose expelled from hence into a world
1	of woe and sorrow sternly he pronounced
1	the rigid interdiction which resounds
1	yet dreadful in mine ear though in my choice
1	not to incur but soon his clear aspect
1	returned and gracious purpose thus renewed 
1	 not only these fair bounds but all the earth
1	to thee and to thy race i give as lords
1	possess it and all things that therein live 
1	or live in sea or air beast fish and fowl 
1	in sign whereof each bird and beast behold
1	after their kinds i bring them to receive
1	from thee their names and pay thee fealty
1	with low subjection understand the same
1	of fish within their watery residence 
1	not hither summoned since they cannot change
1	their element to draw the thinner air 
1	as thus he spake each bird and beast behold
1	approaching two and two these cowering low
1	with blandishment each bird stooped on his wing 
1	i named them as they passed and understood
1	their nature with such knowledge god endued
1	my sudden apprehension but in these
1	i found not what methought i wanted still 
1	and to the heavenly vision thus presumed 
1	o by what name for thou above all these 
1	above mankind or aught than mankind higher 
1	surpassest far my naming how may i
1	adore thee author of this universe 
1	and all this good to man for whose well being
1	so amply and with hands so liberal 
1	thou hast provided all things but with me
1	i see not who partakes in solitude
1	what happiness who can enjoy alone 
1	or all enjoying what contentment find 
1	thus i presumptuous and the vision bright 
1	as with a smile more brightened thus replied 
1	what callest thou solitude is not the earth
1	with various living creatures and the air
1	replenished and all these at thy command
1	to come and play before thee knowest thou not
1	their language and their ways they also know 
1	and reason not contemptibly with these
1	find pastime and bear rule thy realm is large 
1	so spake the universal lord and seemed
1	so ordering i with leave of speech implored 
1	and humble deprecation thus replied 
1	let not my words offend thee heavenly power 
1	my maker be propitious while i speak 
1	hast thou not made me here thy substitute 
1	and these inferiour far beneath me set 
1	among unequals what society
1	can sort what harmony or true delight 
1	which must be mutual in proportion due
1	given and received but in disparity
1	the one intense the other still remiss 
1	cannot well suit with either but soon prove
1	tedious alike of fellowship i speak
1	such as i seek fit to participate
1	all rational delight wherein the brute
1	cannot be human consort they rejoice
1	each with their kind lion with lioness 
1	so fitly them in pairs thou hast combined 
1	much less can bird with beast or fish with fowl
1	so well converse nor with the ox the ape 
1	worse then can man with beast and least of all 
1	whereto the almighty answered not displeased 
1	a nice and subtle happiness i see 
1	thou to thyself proposest in the choice
1	of thy associates adam and wilt taste
1	no pleasure though in pleasure solitary 
1	what thinkest thou then of me and this my state 
1	seem i to thee sufficiently possessed
1	of happiness or not who am alone
1	from all eternity for none i know
1	second to me or like equal much less 
1	how have i then with whom to hold converse 
1	save with the creatures which i made and those
1	to me inferiour infinite descents
1	beneath what other creatures are to thee 
1	he ceased i lowly answered to attain
1	the highth and depth of thy eternal ways
1	all human thoughts come short supreme of things 
1	thou in thyself art perfect and in thee
1	is no deficience found not so is man 
1	but in degree the cause of his desire
1	by conversation with his like to help
1	or solace his defects no need that thou
1	shouldst propagate already infinite 
1	and through all numbers absolute though one 
1	but man by number is to manifest
1	his single imperfection and beget
1	like of his like his image multiplied 
1	in unity defective which requires
1	collateral love and dearest amity 
1	thou in thy secresy although alone 
1	best with thyself accompanied seekest not
1	social communication yet so pleased 
1	canst raise thy creature to what highth thou wilt
1	of union or communion deified 
1	i by conversing cannot these erect
1	from prone nor in their ways complacence find 
1	thus i emboldened spake and freedom used
1	permissive and acceptance found which gained
1	this answer from the gracious voice divine 
1	thus far to try thee adam i was pleased 
1	and find thee knowing not of beasts alone 
1	which thou hast rightly named but of thyself 
1	expressing well the spirit within thee free 
1	my image not imparted to the brute 
1	whose fellowship therefore unmeet for thee
1	good reason was thou freely shouldst dislike 
1	and be so minded still i ere thou spakest 
1	knew it not good for man to be alone 
1	and no such company as then thou sawest
1	intended thee for trial only brought 
1	to see how thou couldest judge of fit and meet 
1	what next i bring shall please thee be assured 
1	thy likeness thy fit help thy other self 
1	thy wish exactly to thy heart s desire 
1	he ended or i heard no more for now
1	my earthly by his heavenly overpowered 
1	which it had long stood under strained to the highth
1	in that celestial colloquy sublime 
1	as with an object that excels the sense
1	dazzled and spent sunk down and sought repair
1	of sleep which instantly fell on me called
1	by nature as in aid and closed mine eyes 
1	mine eyes he closed but open left the cell
1	of fancy my internal sight by which 
1	abstract as in a trance methought i saw 
1	though sleeping where i lay and saw the shape
1	still glorious before whom awake i stood 
1	who stooping opened my left side and took
1	from thence a rib with cordial spirits warm 
1	and life blood streaming fresh wide was the wound 
1	but suddenly with flesh filled up and healed 
1	the rib he formed and fashioned with his hands 
1	under his forming hands a creature grew 
1	man like but different sex so lovely fair 
1	that what seemed fair in all the world seemed now
1	mean or in her summed up in her contained
1	and in her looks which from that time infused
1	sweetness into my heart unfelt before 
1	and into all things from her air inspired
1	the spirit of love and amorous delight 
1	she disappeared and left me dark i waked
1	to find her or for ever to deplore
1	her loss and other pleasures all abjure 
1	when out of hope behold her not far off 
1	such as i saw her in my dream adorned
1	with what all earth or heaven could bestow
1	to make her amiable on she came 
1	led by her heavenly maker though unseen 
1	and guided by his voice nor uninformed
1	of nuptial sanctity and marriage rites 
1	grace was in all her steps heaven in her eye 
1	in every gesture dignity and love 
1	i overjoyed could not forbear aloud 
1	this turn hath made amends thou hast fulfilled
1	thy words creator bounteous and benign 
1	giver of all things fair but fairest this
1	of all thy gifts nor enviest i now see
1	bone of my bone flesh of my flesh myself
1	before me woman is her name of man
1	extracted for this cause he shall forego
1	father and mother and to his wife adhere 
1	and they shall be one flesh one heart one soul 
1	she heard me thus and though divinely brought 
1	yet innocence and virgin modesty 
1	her virtue and the conscience of her worth 
1	that would be wooed and not unsought be won 
1	not obvious not obtrusive but retired 
1	the more desirable or to say all 
1	nature herself though pure of sinful thought 
1	wrought in her so that seeing me she turned 
1	i followed her she what was honour knew 
1	and with obsequious majesty approved
1	my pleaded reason to the nuptial bower
1	i led her blushing like the morn all heaven 
1	and happy constellations on that hour
1	shed their selectest influence the earth
1	gave sign of gratulation and each hill 
1	joyous the birds fresh gales and gentle airs
