1	on his hill top to light the bridal lamp 
1	thus have i told thee all my state and brought
1	my story to the sum of earthly bliss 
1	which i enjoy and must confess to find
1	in all things else delight indeed but such
1	as used or not works in the mind no change 
1	nor vehement desire these delicacies
1	i mean of taste sight smell herbs fruits and flowers 
1	walks and the melody of birds but here
1	far otherwise transported i behold 
1	transported touch here passion first i felt 
1	commotion strange in all enjoyments else
1	superiour and unmoved here only weak
1	against the charm of beauty s powerful glance 
1	or nature failed in me and left some part
1	not proof enough such object to sustain 
1	or from my side subducting took perhaps
1	more than enough at least on her bestowed
1	too much of ornament in outward show
1	elaborate of inward less exact 
1	for well i understand in the prime end
1	of nature her the inferiour in the mind
1	and inward faculties which most excel 
1	in outward also her resembling less
1	his image who made both and less expressing
1	the character of that dominion given
1	o er other creatures yet when i approach
1	her loveliness so absolute she seems
1	and in herself complete so well to know
1	her own that what she wills to do or say 
1	seems wisest virtuousest discreetest best 
1	all higher knowledge in her presence falls
1	degraded wisdom in discourse with her
1	loses discountenanced and like folly shows 
1	authority and reason on her wait 
1	as one intended first not after made
1	occasionally and to consummate all 
1	greatness of mind and nobleness their seat
1	build in her loveliest and create an awe
1	about her as a guard angelick placed 
1	to whom the angel with contracted brow 
1	accuse not nature she hath done her part 
1	do thou but thine and be not diffident
1	of wisdom she deserts thee not if thou
1	dismiss not her when most thou needest her nigh 
1	by attributing overmuch to things
1	less excellent as thou thyself perceivest 
1	for what admirest thou what transports thee so 
1	an outside fair no doubt and worthy well
1	thy cherishing thy honouring and thy love 
1	not thy subjection weigh with her thyself 
1	then value oft times nothing profits more
1	than self esteem grounded on just and right
1	well managed of that skill the more thou knowest 
1	the more she will acknowledge thee her head 
1	and to realities yield all her shows 
