1	empress of this fair world resplendent eve 
1	easy to me it is to tell thee all
1	what thou commandest and right thou shouldst be obeyed 
1	i was at first as other beasts that graze
1	the trodden herb of abject thoughts and low 
1	as was my food nor aught but food discerned
1	or sex and apprehended nothing high 
1	till on a day roving the field i chanced
1	a goodly tree far distant to behold
1	loaden with fruit of fairest colours mixed 
1	ruddy and gold i nearer drew to gaze 
1	when from the boughs a savoury odour blown 
1	grateful to appetite more pleased my sense
1	than smell of sweetest fennel or the teats
1	of ewe or goat dropping with milk at even 
1	unsucked of lamb or kid that tend their play 
1	to satisfy the sharp desire i had
1	of tasting those fair apples i resolved
1	not to defer hunger and thirst at once 
1	powerful persuaders quickened at the scent
1	of that alluring fruit urged me so keen 
1	about the mossy trunk i wound me soon 
1	for high from ground the branches would require
