1	o sacred wise and wisdom giving plant 
1	mother of science now i feel thy power
1	within me clear not only to discern
1	things in their causes but to trace the ways
1	of highest agents deemed however wise 
1	queen of this universe do not believe
1	those rigid threats of death ye shall not die 
1	how should you by the fruit it gives you life
1	to knowledge by the threatener look on me 
1	me who have touched and tasted yet both live 
1	and life more perfect have attained than fate
1	meant me by venturing higher than my lot 
1	shall that be shut to man which to the beast
1	is open or will god incense his ire
1	for such a petty trespass and not praise
1	rather your dauntless virtue whom the pain
1	of death denounced whatever thing death be 
1	deterred not from achieving what might lead
1	to happier life knowledge of good and evil 
1	of good how just of evil if what is evil
1	be real why not known since easier shunned 
1	god therefore cannot hurt ye and be just 
1	not just not god not feared then nor obeyed 
1	your fear itself of death removes the fear 
1	why then was this forbid why but to awe 
1	why but to keep ye low and ignorant 
1	his worshippers he knows that in the day
1	ye eat thereof your eyes that seem so clear 
1	yet are but dim shall perfectly be then
1	opened and cleared and ye shall be as gods 
1	knowing both good and evil as they know 
1	that ye shall be as gods since i as man 
1	internal man is but proportion meet 
1	i of brute human ye of human gods 
1	so ye shall die perhaps by putting off
1	human to put on gods death to be wished 
1	though threatened which no worse than this can bring 
1	and what are gods that man may not become
1	as they participating god like food 
1	the gods are first and that advantage use
1	on our belief that all from them proceeds 
1	i question it for this fair earth i see 
1	warmed by the sun producing every kind 
1	them nothing if they all things who enclosed
1	knowledge of good and evil in this tree 
1	that whoso eats thereof forthwith attains
1	wisdom without their leave and wherein lies
1	the offence that man should thus attain to know 
1	what can your knowledge hurt him or this tree
1	impart against his will if all be his 
1	or is it envy and can envy dwell
1	in heavenly breasts these these and many more
1	causes import your need of this fair fruit 
1	goddess humane reach then and freely taste 
1	he ended and his words replete with guile 
1	into her heart too easy entrance won 
1	fixed on the fruit she gazed which to behold
1	might tempt alone and in her ears the sound
1	yet rung of his persuasive words impregned
1	with reason to her seeming and with truth 
1	mean while the hour of noon drew on and waked
1	an eager appetite raised by the smell
1	so savoury of that fruit which with desire 
1	inclinable now grown to touch or taste 
1	solicited her longing eye yet first
1	pausing a while thus to herself she mused 
1	great are thy virtues doubtless best of fruits 
1	though kept from man and worthy to be admired 
1	whose taste too long forborn at first assay
1	gave elocution to the mute and taught
1	the tongue not made for speech to speak thy praise 
1	thy praise he also who forbids thy use 
1	conceals not from us naming thee the tree
1	of knowledge knowledge both of good and evil 
1	forbids us then to taste but his forbidding
1	commends thee more while it infers the good
1	by thee communicated and our want 
1	for good unknown sure is not had or had
1	and yet unknown is as not had at all 
1	in plain then what forbids he but to know 
1	forbids us good forbids us to be wise 
1	such prohibitions bind not but if death
1	bind us with after bands what profits then
1	our inward freedom in the day we eat
1	of this fair fruit our doom is we shall die 
1	how dies the serpent he hath eaten and lives 
1	and knows and speaks and reasons and discerns 
1	irrational till then for us alone
1	was death invented or to us denied
