1	on me as on their natural center light
1	heavy though in their place o fleeting joys
1	of paradise dear bought with lasting woes 
1	did i request thee maker from my clay
1	to mould me man did i solicit thee
1	from darkness to promote me or here place
1	in this delicious garden as my will
1	concurred not to my being it were but right
1	and equal to reduce me to my dust 
1	desirous to resign and render back
1	all i received unable to perform
1	thy terms too hard by which i was to hold
1	the good i sought not to the loss of that 
1	sufficient penalty why hast thou added
1	the sense of endless woes inexplicable
1	thy justice seems yet to say truth too late
1	i thus contest then should have been refused
1	those terms whatever when they were proposed 
1	thou didst accept them wilt thou enjoy the good 
1	then cavil the conditions and though god
1	made thee without thy leave what if thy son
1	prove disobedient and reproved retort 
1	 wherefore didst thou beget me i sought it not 
