1	mortality my sentence and be earth
1	insensible how glad would lay me down
1	as in my mother s lap there i should rest 
1	and sleep secure his dreadful voice no more
1	would thunder in my ears no fear of worse
1	to me and to my offspring would torment me
1	with cruel expectation yet one doubt
1	pursues me still lest all i cannot die 
1	lest that pure breath of life the spirit of man
1	which god inspired cannot together perish
1	with this corporeal clod then in the grave 
1	or in some other dismal place who knows
1	but i shall die a living death o thought
1	horrid if true yet why it was but breath
1	of life that sinned what dies but what had life
1	and sin the body properly had neither 
1	all of me then shall die let this appease
1	the doubt since human reach no further knows 
1	for though the lord of all be infinite 
1	is his wrath also be it man is not so 
1	but mortal doomed how can he exercise
1	wrath without end on man whom death must end 
1	can he make deathless death that were to make
1	strange contradiction which to god himself
1	impossible is held as argument
1	of weakness not of power will he draw out 
1	for anger s sake finite to infinite 
1	in punished man to satisfy his rigour 
1	satisfied never that were to extend
1	his sentence beyond dust and nature s law 
1	by which all causes else according still
1	to the reception of their matter act 
1	not to the extent of their own sphere but say
1	that death be not one stroke as i supposed 
1	bereaving sense but endless misery
1	from this day onward which i feel begun
1	both in me and without me and so last
1	to perpetuity ay me that fear
1	comes thundering back with dreadful revolution
