1	am found eternal and incorporate both 
1	nor i on my part single in me all
1	posterity stands cursed fair patrimony
1	that i must leave ye sons o were i able
1	to waste it all myself and leave ye none 
1	so disinherited how would you bless
1	me now your curse ah why should all mankind 
1	for one man s fault thus guiltless be condemned 
1	it guiltless but from me what can proceed 
1	but all corrupt both mind and will depraved
1	not to do only but to will the same
1	with me how can they then acquitted stand
1	in sight of god him after all disputes 
1	forced i absolve all my evasions vain 
1	and reasonings though through mazes lead me still
1	but to my own conviction first and last
1	on me me only as the source and spring
1	of all corruption all the blame lights due 
1	so might the wrath fond wish couldst thou support
1	that burden heavier than the earth to bear 
1	than all the world much heavier though divided
1	with that bad woman thus what thou desirest 
1	and what thou fearest alike destroys all hope
1	of refuge and concludes thee miserable
1	beyond all past example and future 
1	to satan only like both crime and doom 
1	o conscience into what abyss of fears
1	and horrours hast thou driven me out of which
1	i find no way from deep to deeper plunged 
1	thus adam to himself lamented loud 
1	through the still night not now as ere man fell 
1	wholesome and cool and mild but with black air
1	accompanied with damps and dreadful gloom 
1	which to his evil conscience represented
1	all things with double terrour on the ground
1	outstretched he lay on the cold ground and oft
1	cursed his creation death as oft accused
1	the day of his offence why comes not death 
1	said he with one thrice acceptable stroke
