1	to agra and lahor of great mogul 
1	down to the golden chersonese or where
1	the persian in ecbatan sat or since
1	in hispahan or where the russian ksar
1	turchestan born nor could his eye not ken
1	the empire of negus to his utmost port
1	ercoco and the less maritim kings
1	and sofala thought ophir to the realm
1	of congo and angola farthest south 
1	or thence from niger flood to atlas mount
1	the kingdoms of almansor fez and sus 
1	on europe thence and where rome was to sway
1	the world in spirit perhaps he also saw
1	rich mexico the seat of montezume 
1	and cusco in peru the richer seat
1	of atabalipa and yet unspoiled
1	guiana whose great city geryon s sons
1	call el dorado but to nobler sights
1	michael from adam s eyes the film removed 
1	which that false fruit that promised clearer sight
1	had bred then purged with euphrasy and rue
1	the visual nerve for he had much to see 
1	and from the well of life three drops instilled 
1	so deep the power of these ingredients pierced 
1	even to the inmost seat of mental sight 
1	that adam now enforced to close his eyes 
1	sunk down and all his spirits became entranced 
1	but him the gentle angel by the hand
1	soon raised and his attention thus recalled 
1	adam now ope thine eyes and first behold
1	the effects which thy original crime hath wrought
1	in some to spring from thee who never touched
1	the excepted tree nor with the snake conspired 
1	nor sinned thy sin yet from that sin derive
1	corruption to bring forth more violent deeds 
1	his eyes he opened and beheld a field 
1	part arable and tilth whereon were sheaves
1	new reaped the other part sheep walks and folds 
1	i the midst an altar as the land mark stood 
1	rustick of grassy sord thither anon
1	a sweaty reaper from his tillage brought
1	first fruits the green ear and the yellow sheaf 
1	unculled as came to hand a shepherd next 
1	more meek came with the firstlings of his flock 
1	choicest and best then sacrificing laid
1	the inwards and their fat with incense strowed 
1	on the cleft wood and all due rights performed 
1	his offering soon propitious fire from heaven
1	consumed with nimble glance and grateful steam 
1	the other s not for his was not sincere 
1	whereat he inly raged and as they talked 
1	smote him into the midriff with a stone
1	that beat out life he fell and deadly pale 
1	groaned out his soul with gushing blood effused 
1	much at that sight was adam in his heart
1	dismayed and thus in haste to the angel cried 
1	o teacher some great mischief hath befallen
1	to that meek man who well had sacrificed 
1	is piety thus and pure devotion paid 
1	to whom michael thus he also moved replied 
1	these two are brethren adam and to come
1	out of thy loins the unjust the just hath slain 
1	for envy that his brother s offering found
1	from heaven acceptance but the bloody fact
1	will be avenged and the other s faith approved 
1	lose no reward though here thou see him die 
1	rolling in dust and gore to which our sire 
1	alas both for the deed and for the cause 
1	but have i now seen death is this the way
1	i must return to native dust o sight
1	of terrour foul and ugly to behold 
1	horrid to think how horrible to feel 
1	to whom thus michael death thou hast seen
1	in his first shape on man but many shapes
1	of death and many are the ways that lead
1	to his grim cave all dismal yet to sense
1	more terrible at the entrance than within 
1	some as thou sawest by violent stroke shall die 
1	by fire flood famine by intemperance more
1	in meats and drinks which on the earth shall bring
1	diseases dire of which a monstrous crew
1	before thee shall appear that thou mayest know
1	what misery the inabstinence of eve
1	shall bring on men immediately a place
1	before his eyes appeared sad noisome dark 
1	a lazar house it seemed wherein were laid
1	numbers of all diseased all maladies
1	of ghastly spasm or racking torture qualms
1	of heart sick agony all feverous kinds 
1	convulsions epilepsies fierce catarrhs 
1	intestine stone and ulcer colick pangs 
1	demoniack phrenzy moaping melancholy 
1	and moon struck madness pining atrophy 
1	marasmus and wide wasting pestilence 
1	dropsies and asthmas and joint racking rheums 
1	dire was the tossing deep the groans despair
1	tended the sick busiest from couch to couch 
1	and over them triumphant death his dart
1	shook but delayed to strike though oft invoked
1	with vows as their chief good and final hope 
1	sight so deform what heart of rock could long
1	dry eyed behold adam could not but wept 
1	though not of woman born compassion quelled
1	his best of man and gave him up to tears
1	a space till firmer thoughts restrained excess 
1	and scarce recovering words his plaint renewed 
1	o miserable mankind to what fall
1	degraded to what wretched state reserved 
1	better end here unborn why is life given
1	to be thus wrested from us rather why
1	obtruded on us thus who if we knew
1	what we receive would either no accept
1	life offered or soon beg to lay it down 
1	glad to be so dismissed in peace can thus
1	the image of god in man created once
1	so goodly and erect though faulty since 
1	to such unsightly sufferings be debased
1	under inhuman pains why should not man 
1	retaining still divine similitude
1	in part from such deformities be free 
1	and for his maker s image sake exempt 
1	their maker s image answered michael then
1	forsook them when themselves they vilified
1	to serve ungoverned appetite and took
1	his image whom they served a brutish vice 
1	inductive mainly to the sin of eve 
1	therefore so abject is their punishment 
1	disfiguring not god s likeness but their own 
1	or if his likeness by themselves defaced 
1	while they pervert pure nature s healthful rules
1	to loathsome sickness worthily since they
1	god s image did not reverence in themselves 
1	i yield it just said adam and submit 
1	but is there yet no other way besides
1	these painful passages how we may come
1	to death and mix with our connatural dust 
1	there is said michael if thou well observe
1	the rule of not too much by temperance taught 
1	in what thou eatest and drinkest seeking from thence
1	due nourishment not gluttonous delight 
1	till many years over thy head return 
1	so mayest thou live till like ripe fruit thou drop
1	into thy mother s lap or be with ease
1	gathered nor harshly plucked for death mature 
1	this is old age but then thou must outlive
1	thy youth thy strength thy beauty which will change
1	to withered weak and gray thy senses then 
1	obtuse all taste of pleasure must forego 
1	to what thou hast and for the air of youth 
1	hopeful and cheerful in thy blood will reign
1	a melancholy damp of cold and dry
1	to weigh thy spirits down and last consume
1	the balm of life to whom our ancestor 
1	henceforth i fly not death nor would prolong
1	life much bent rather how i may be quit 
1	fairest and easiest of this cumbrous charge 
1	which i must keep till my appointed day
1	of rendering up and patiently attend
1	my dissolution michael replied 
1	nor love thy life nor hate but what thou livest
1	live well how long or short permit to heaven 
1	and now prepare thee for another sight 
1	he looked and saw a spacious plain whereon
1	were tents of various hue by some were herds
1	of cattle grazing others whence the sound
1	of instruments that made melodious chime 
1	was heard of harp and organ and who moved
1	their stops and chords was seen his volant touch 
1	instinct through all proportions low and high 
1	fled and pursued transverse the resonant fugue 
1	in other part stood one who at the forge
1	labouring two massy clods of iron and brass
1	had melted whether found where casual fire
1	had wasted woods on mountain or in vale 
1	down to the veins of earth thence gliding hot
1	to some cave s mouth or whether washed by stream
1	from underground the liquid ore he drained
1	into fit moulds prepared from which he formed
1	first his own tools then what might else be wrought
1	fusil or graven in metal after these 
1	but on the hither side a different sort
1	from the high neighbouring hills which was their seat 
1	down to the plain descended by their guise
1	just men they seemed and all their study bent
1	to worship god aright and know his works
1	not hid nor those things last which might preserve
1	freedom and peace to men they on the plain
1	long had not walked when from the tents behold 
1	a bevy of fair women richly gay
1	in gems and wanton dress to the harp they sung
1	soft amorous ditties and in dance came on 
1	the men though grave eyed them and let their eyes
1	rove without rein till in the amorous net
1	fast caught they liked and each his liking chose 
1	and now of love they treat till the evening star 
1	love s harbinger appeared then all in heat
1	they light the nuptial torch and bid invoke
1	hymen then first to marriage rites invoked 
1	with feast and musick all the tents resound 
1	such happy interview and fair event
1	of love and youth not lost songs garlands flowers 
1	and charming symphonies attached the heart
1	of adam soon inclined to admit delight 
1	the bent of nature which he thus expressed 
1	true opener of mine eyes prime angel blest 
1	much better seems this vision and more hope
1	of peaceful days portends than those two past 
1	those were of hate and death or pain much worse 
1	here nature seems fulfilled in all her ends 
1	to whom thus michael judge not what is best
1	by pleasure though to nature seeming meet 
1	created as thou art to nobler end
1	holy and pure conformity divine 
1	those tents thou sawest so pleasant were the tents
1	of wickedness wherein shall dwell his race
1	who slew his brother studious they appear
1	of arts that polish life inventers rare 
1	unmindful of their maker though his spirit
1	taught them but they his gifts acknowledged none 
1	yet they a beauteous offspring shall beget 
1	for that fair female troop thou sawest that seemed
1	of goddesses so blithe so smooth so gay 
1	yet empty of all good wherein consists
1	woman s domestick honour and chief praise 
1	bred only and completed to the taste
1	of lustful appetence to sing to dance 
1	to dress and troll the tongue and roll the eye 
1	to these that sober race of men whose lives
1	religious titled them the sons of god 
1	shall yield up all their virtue all their fame
1	ignobly to the trains and to the smiles
1	of these fair atheists and now swim in joy 
1	erelong to swim at large and laugh for which
1	the world erelong a world of tears must weep 
1	to whom thus adam of short joy bereft 
1	o pity and shame that they who to live well
1	entered so fair should turn aside to tread
1	paths indirect or in the mid way faint 
1	but still i see the tenour of man s woe
1	holds on the same from woman to begin 
1	from man s effeminate slackness it begins 
1	said the angel who should better hold his place
1	by wisdom and superiour gifts received 
1	but now prepare thee for another scene 
1	he looked and saw wide territory spread
1	before him towns and rural works between 
1	cities of men with lofty gates and towers 
1	concourse in arms fierce faces threatening war 
1	giants of mighty bone and bold emprise 
1	part wield their arms part curb the foaming steed 
1	single or in array of battle ranged
1	both horse and foot nor idly mustering stood 
1	one way a band select from forage drives
1	a herd of beeves fair oxen and fair kine 
1	from a fat meadow ground or fleecy flock 
1	ewes and their bleating lambs over the plain 
1	their booty scarce with life the shepherds fly 
1	but call in aid which makes a bloody fray 
1	with cruel tournament the squadrons join 
1	where cattle pastured late now scattered lies
1	with carcasses and arms the ensanguined field 
1	deserted others to a city strong
1	lay siege encamped by battery scale and mine 
1	assaulting others from the wall defend
1	with dart and javelin stones and sulphurous fire 
1	on each hand slaughter and gigantick deeds 
1	in other part the sceptered heralds call
1	to council in the city gates anon
1	gray headed men and grave with warriours mixed 
1	assemble and harangues are heard but soon 
1	in factious opposition till at last 
1	of middle age one rising eminent
1	in wise deport spake much of right and wrong 
1	of justice or religion truth and peace 
1	and judgement from above him old and young
1	exploded and had seized with violent hands 
1	had not a cloud descending snatched him thence
1	unseen amid the throng so violence
1	proceeded and oppression and sword law 
1	through all the plain and refuge none was found 
1	adam was all in tears and to his guide
1	lamenting turned full sad o what are these 
1	death s ministers not men who thus deal death
1	inhumanly to men and multiply
1	ten thousandfold the sin of him who slew
1	his brother for of whom such massacre
1	make they but of their brethren men of men
1	but who was that just man whom had not heaven
1	rescued had in his righteousness been lost 
1	to whom thus michael these are the product
1	of those ill mated marriages thou sawest 
1	where good with bad were matched who of themselves
1	abhor to join and by imprudence mixed 
1	produce prodigious births of body or mind 
1	such were these giants men of high renown 
1	for in those days might only shall be admired 
1	and valour and heroick virtue called 
1	to overcome in battle and subdue
1	nations and bring home spoils with infinite
1	man slaughter shall be held the highest pitch
1	of human glory and for glory done
1	of triumph to be styled great conquerours
1	patrons of mankind gods and sons of gods 
1	destroyers rightlier called and plagues of men 
1	thus fame shall be achieved renown on earth 
1	and what most merits fame in silence hid 
1	but he the seventh from thee whom thou beheldst
1	the only righteous in a world preverse 
1	and therefore hated therefore so beset
1	with foes for daring single to be just 
1	and utter odious truth that god would come
1	to judge them with his saints him the most high
1	rapt in a balmy cloud with winged steeds
1	did as thou sawest receive to walk with god
1	high in salvation and the climes of bliss 
1	exempt from death to show thee what reward
1	awaits the good the rest what punishment 
1	which now direct thine eyes and soon behold 
1	he looked and saw the face of things quite changed 
1	the brazen throat of war had ceased to roar 
1	all now was turned to jollity and game 
1	to luxury and riot feast and dance 
1	marrying or prostituting as befel 
1	rape or adultery where passing fair
1	allured them thence from cups to civil broils 
1	at length a reverend sire among them came 
1	and of their doings great dislike declared 
1	and testified against their ways he oft
1	frequented their assemblies whereso met 
1	triumphs or festivals and to them preached
1	conversion and repentance as to souls
1	in prison under judgements imminent 
1	but all in vain which when he saw he ceased
1	contending and removed his tents far off 
1	then from the mountain hewing timber tall 
1	began to build a vessel of huge bulk 
1	measured by cubit length and breadth and highth 
1	smeared round with pitch and in the side a door
1	contrived and of provisions laid in large 
1	for man and beast when lo a wonder strange 
1	of every beast and bird and insect small 
1	came sevens and pairs and entered in as taught
1	their order last the sire and his three sons 
1	with their four wives and god made fast the door 
1	mean while the south wind rose and with black wings
1	wide hovering all the clouds together drove
1	from under heaven the hills to their supply
1	vapour and exhalation dusk and moist 
1	sent up amain and now the thickened sky
1	like a dark ceiling stood down rushed the rain
1	impetuous and continued till the earth
1	no more was seen the floating vessel swum
1	uplifted and secure with beaked prow
1	rode tilting o er the waves all dwellings else
1	flood overwhelmed and them with all their pomp
1	deep under water rolled sea covered sea 
1	sea without shore and in their palaces 
1	where luxury late reigned sea monsters whelped
1	and stabled of mankind so numerous late 
1	all left in one small bottom swum imbarked 
1	how didst thou grieve then adam to behold
1	the end of all thy offspring end so sad 
1	depopulation thee another flood 
1	of tears and sorrow a flood thee also drowned 
1	and sunk thee as thy sons till gently reared
1	by the angel on thy feet thou stoodest at last 
1	though comfortless as when a father mourns
1	his children all in view destroyed at once 
1	and scarce to the angel utter dst thus thy plaint 
1	o visions ill foreseen better had i
1	lived ignorant of future so had borne
1	my part of evil only each day s lot
1	enough to bear those now that were dispensed
1	the burden of many ages on me light
1	at once by my foreknowledge gaining birth
1	abortive to torment me ere their being 
1	with thought that they must be let no man seek
1	henceforth to be foretold what shall befall
1	him or his children evil he may be sure 
1	which neither his foreknowing can prevent 
1	and he the future evil shall no less
1	in apprehension than in substance feel 
1	grievous to bear but that care now is past 
1	man is not whom to warn those few escaped
1	famine and anguish will at last consume 
1	wandering that watery desart i had hope 
1	when violence was ceased and war on earth 
1	all would have then gone well peace would have crowned
1	with length of happy days the race of man 
1	but i was far deceived for now i see
1	peace to corrupt no less than war to waste 
1	how comes it thus unfold celestial guide 
1	and whether here the race of man will end 
1	to whom thus michael those whom last thou sawest
1	in triumph and luxurious wealth are they
1	first seen in acts of prowess eminent
1	and great exploits but of true virtue void 
1	who having spilt much blood and done much wast
1	subduing nations and achieved thereby
1	fame in the world high titles and rich prey 
1	shall change their course to pleasure ease and sloth 
1	surfeit and lust till wantonness and pride
1	raise out of friendship hostile deeds in peace 
1	the conquered also and enslaved by war 
1	shall with their freedom lost all virtue lose
1	and fear of god from whom their piety feigned
1	in sharp contest of battle found no aid
1	against invaders therefore cooled in zeal 
1	thenceforth shall practice how to live secure 
1	worldly or dissolute on what their lords
1	shall leave them to enjoy for the earth shall bear
1	more than enough that temperance may be tried 
1	so all shall turn degenerate all depraved 
1	justice and temperance truth and faith forgot 
1	one man except the only son of light
1	in a dark age against example good 
1	against allurement custom and a world
1	offended fearless of reproach and scorn 
1	or violence he of their wicked ways
1	shall them admonish and before them set
1	the paths of righteousness how much more safe
1	and full of peace denouncing wrath to come
1	on their impenitence and shall return
1	of them derided but of god observed
1	the one just man alive by his command
1	shall build a wonderous ark as thou beheldst 
1	to save himself and houshold from amidst
1	a world devote to universal wrack 
1	no sooner he with them of man and beast
1	select for life shall in the ark be lodged 
1	and sheltered round but all the cataracts
1	of heaven set open on the earth shall pour
1	rain day and night all fountains of the deep 
1	broke up shall heave the ocean to usurp
1	beyond all bounds till inundation rise
1	above the highest hills then shall this mount
1	of paradise by might of waves be moved
1	out of his place pushed by the horned flood 
1	with all his verdure spoiled and trees adrift 
1	down the great river to the opening gulf 
1	and there take root an island salt and bare 
1	the haunt of seals and orcs and sea mews clang 
1	to teach thee that god attributes to place
1	no sanctity if none be thither brought
1	by men who there frequent or therein dwell 
1	and now what further shall ensue behold 
1	he looked and saw the ark hull on the flood 
1	which now abated for the clouds were fled 
1	driven by a keen north wind that blowing dry 
1	wrinkled the face of deluge as decayed 
1	and the clear sun on his wide watery glass
1	gazed hot and of the fresh wave largely drew 
1	as after thirst which made their flowing shrink
1	from standing lake to tripping ebb that stole
1	with soft foot towards the deep who now had stopt
1	his sluces as the heaven his windows shut 
1	the ark no more now floats but seems on ground 
1	fast on the top of some high mountain fixed 
1	and now the tops of hills as rocks appear 
1	with clamour thence the rapid currents drive 
1	towards the retreating sea their furious tide 
1	forthwith from out the ark a raven flies 
1	and after him the surer messenger 
1	a dove sent forth once and again to spy
1	green tree or ground whereon his foot may light 
1	the second time returning in his bill
1	an olive leaf he brings pacifick sign 
1	anon dry ground appears and from his ark
1	the ancient sire descends with all his train 
1	then with uplifted hands and eyes devout 
1	grateful to heaven over his head beholds
1	a dewy cloud and in the cloud a bow
1	conspicuous with three lifted colours gay 
1	betokening peace from god and covenant new 
1	whereat the heart of adam erst so sad 
1	greatly rejoiced and thus his joy broke forth 
1	o thou who future things canst represent
1	as present heavenly instructer i revive
1	at this last sight assured that man shall live 
1	with all the creatures and their seed preserve 
1	far less i now lament for one whole world
1	of wicked sons destroyed than i rejoice
1	for one man found so perfect and so just 
1	that god vouchsafes to raise another world
1	from him and all his anger to forget 
1	but say what mean those coloured streaks in heaven
1	distended as the brow of god appeased 
1	or serve they as a flowery verge to bind
1	the fluid skirts of that same watery cloud 
1	lest it again dissolve and shower the earth 
1	to whom the arch angel dextrously thou aimest 
1	so willingly doth god remit his ire 
1	though late repenting him of man depraved 
1	grieved at his heart when looking down he saw
1	the whole earth filled with violence and all flesh
1	corrupting each their way yet those removed 
1	such grace shall one just man find in his sight 
1	that he relents not to blot out mankind 
1	and makes a covenant never to destroy
1	the earth again by flood nor let the sea
1	surpass his bounds nor rain to drown the world 
1	with man therein or beast but when he brings
1	over the earth a cloud will therein set
1	his triple coloured bow whereon to look 
1	and call to mind his covenant day and night 
1	seed time and harvest heat and hoary frost 
1	shall hold their course till fire purge all things new 
1	both heaven and earth wherein the just shall dwell 
1	as one who in his journey bates at noon 
1	though bent on speed so here the arch angel paused
1	betwixt the world destroyed and world restored 
1	if adam aught perhaps might interpose 
1	then with transition sweet new speech resumes 
1	thus thou hast seen one world begin and end 
1	and man as from a second stock proceed 
1	much thou hast yet to see but i perceive
1	thy mortal sight to fail objects divine
1	must needs impair and weary human sense 
1	henceforth what is to come i will relate 
1	thou therefore give due audience and attend 
1	this second source of men while yet but few 
1	and while the dread of judgement past remains
1	fresh in their minds fearing the deity 
1	with some regard to what is just and right
1	shall lead their lives and multiply apace 
1	labouring the soil and reaping plenteous crop 
1	corn wine and oil and from the herd or flock 
1	oft sacrificing bullock lamb or kid 
1	with large wine offerings poured and sacred feast 
1	shall spend their days in joy unblamed and dwell
1	long time in peace by families and tribes 
1	under paternal rule till one shall rise
1	of proud ambitious heart who not content
1	with fair equality fraternal state 
1	will arrogate dominion undeserved
1	over his brethren and quite dispossess
1	concord and law of nature from the earth 
1	hunting and men not beasts shall be his game 
1	with war and hostile snare such as refuse
1	subjection to his empire tyrannous 
1	a mighty hunter thence he shall be styled
1	before the lord as in despite of heaven 
1	or from heaven claiming second sovranty 
1	and from rebellion shall derive his name 
1	though of rebellion others he accuse 
1	he with a crew whom like ambition joins
1	with him or under him to tyrannize 
1	marching from eden towards the west shall find
1	the plain wherein a black bituminous gurge
1	boils out from under ground the mouth of hell 
1	of brick and of that stuff they cast to build
1	a city and tower whose top may reach to heaven 
1	and get themselves a name lest far dispersed
1	in foreign lands their memory be lost 
1	regardless whether good or evil fame 
1	but god who oft descends to visit men
1	unseen and through their habitations walks
1	to mark their doings them beholding soon 
1	comes down to see their city ere the tower
1	obstruct heaven towers and in derision sets
1	upon their tongues a various spirit to rase
1	quite out their native language and instead 
1	to sow a jangling noise of words unknown 
1	forthwith a hideous gabble rises loud 
1	among the builders each to other calls
1	not understood till hoarse and all in rage 
1	as mocked they storm great laughter was in heaven 
1	and looking down to see the hubbub strange 
1	and hear the din thus was the building left
1	ridiculous and the work confusion named 
1	whereto thus adam fatherly displeased 
1	o execrable son so to aspire
1	above his brethren to himself assuming
1	authority usurped from god not given 
1	he gave us only over beast fish fowl 
1	dominion absolute that right we hold
1	by his donation but man over men
1	he made not lord such title to himself
1	reserving human left from human free 
1	but this usurper his encroachment proud
1	stays not on man to god his tower intends
1	siege and defiance wretched man what food
1	will he convey up thither to sustain
1	himself and his rash army where thin air
1	above the clouds will pine his entrails gross 
1	and famish him of breath if not of bread 
1	to whom thus michael justly thou abhorrest
1	that son who on the quiet state of men
1	such trouble brought affecting to subdue
1	rational liberty yet know withal 
1	since thy original lapse true liberty
1	is lost which always with right reason dwells
1	twinned and from her hath no dividual being 
1	reason in man obscured or not obeyed 
1	immediately inordinate desires 
1	and upstart passions catch the government
1	from reason and to servitude reduce
1	man till then free therefore since he permits
1	within himself unworthy powers to reign
1	over free reason god in judgement just 
1	subjects him from without to violent lords 
1	who oft as undeservedly enthrall
1	his outward freedom tyranny must be 
1	though to the tyrant thereby no excuse 
1	yet sometimes nations will decline so low
1	from virtue which is reason that no wrong 
1	but justice and some fatal curse annexed 
1	deprives them of their outward liberty 
1	their inward lost witness the irreverent son
1	of him who built the ark who for the shame
1	done to his father heard this heavy curse 
1	servant of servants on his vicious race 
1	thus will this latter as the former world 
1	still tend from bad to worse till god at last 
1	wearied with their iniquities withdraw
1	his presence from among them and avert
1	his holy eyes resolving from thenceforth
1	to leave them to their own polluted ways 
1	and one peculiar nation to select
1	from all the rest of whom to be invoked 
1	a nation from one faithful man to spring 
1	him on this side euphrates yet residing 
1	bred up in idol worship o that men
1	 canst thou believe should be so stupid grown 
1	while yet the patriarch lived who scaped the flood 
1	as to forsake the living god and fall
1	to worship their own work in wood and stone
1	for gods yet him god the most high vouchsafes
1	to call by vision from his father s house 
1	his kindred and false gods into a land
1	which he will show him and from him will raise
1	a mighty nation and upon him shower
1	his benediction so that in his seed
1	all nations shall be blest he straight obeys 
1	not knowing to what land yet firm believes 
1	i see him but thou canst not with what faith
1	he leaves his gods his friends and native soil 
1	ur of chaldaea passing now the ford
1	to haran after him a cumbrous train
1	of herds and flocks and numerous servitude 
1	not wandering poor but trusting all his wealth
1	with god who called him in a land unknown 
1	canaan he now attains i see his tents
1	pitched about sechem and the neighbouring plain
1	of moreh there by promise he receives
1	gift to his progeny of all that land 
1	from hameth northward to the desart south 
1	 things by their names i call though yet unnamed 
1	from hermon east to the great western sea 
1	mount hermon yonder sea each place behold
1	in prospect as i point them on the shore
1	mount carmel here the double founted stream 
1	jordan true limit eastward but his sons
1	shall dwell to senir that long ridge of hills 
1	this ponder that all nations of the earth
1	shall in his seed be blessed by that seed
1	is meant thy great deliverer who shall bruise
1	the serpent s head whereof to thee anon
1	plainlier shall be revealed this patriarch blest 
1	whom faithful abraham due time shall call 
1	a son and of his son a grand child leaves 
1	like him in faith in wisdom and renown 
1	the grandchild with twelve sons increased departs
1	from canaan to a land hereafter called
1	see where it flows disgorging at seven mouths
1	into the sea to sojourn in that land
1	he comes invited by a younger son
1	in time of dearth a son whose worthy deeds
1	raise him to be the second in that realm
1	of pharaoh there he dies and leaves his race
1	growing into a nation and now grown
1	suspected to a sequent king who seeks
1	to stop their overgrowth as inmate guests
1	too numerous whence of guests he makes them slaves
1	inhospitably and kills their infant males 
1	till by two brethren these two brethren call
1	moses and aaron sent from god to claim
1	his people from enthralment they return 
1	with glory and spoil back to their promised land 
1	but first the lawless tyrant who denies
1	to know their god or message to regard 
1	must be compelled by signs and judgements dire 
1	to blood unshed the rivers must be turned 
1	frogs lice and flies must all his palace fill
1	with loathed intrusion and fill all the land 
1	his cattle must of rot and murren die 
1	botches and blains must all his flesh emboss 
1	and all his people thunder mixed with hail 
1	and wheel on the earth devouring where it rolls 
1	what it devours not herb or fruit or grain 
1	a darksome cloud of locusts swarming down
1	must eat and on the ground leave nothing green 
1	darkness must overshadow all his bounds 
1	palpable darkness and blot out three days 
1	last with one midnight stroke all the first born
1	the river dragon tamed at length submits
1	to let his sojourners depart and oft
1	humbles his stubborn heart but still as ice
1	more hardened after thaw till in his rage
1	pursuing whom he late dismissed the sea
1	swallows him with his host but them lets pass 
1	as on dry land between two crystal walls 
1	awed by the rod of moses so to stand
1	divided till his rescued gain their shore 
1	such wondrous power god to his saint will lend 
1	though present in his angel who shall go
1	before them in a cloud and pillar of fire 
1	by day a cloud by night a pillar of fire 
1	to guide them in their journey and remove
1	behind them while the obdurate king pursues 
1	all night he will pursue but his approach
1	darkness defends between till morning watch 
1	then through the fiery pillar and the cloud 
1	god looking forth will trouble all his host 
1	and craze their chariot wheels when by command
1	moses once more his potent rod extends
1	over the sea the sea his rod obeys 
1	on their embattled ranks the waves return 
1	and overwhelm their war the race elect
1	safe toward canaan from the shore advance
1	through the wild desart not the readiest way 
1	lest entering on the canaanite alarmed 
1	war terrify them inexpert and fear
1	inglorious life with servitude for life
1	to noble and ignoble is more sweet
1	untrained in arms where rashness leads not on 
1	this also shall they gain by their delay
1	in the wide wilderness there they shall found
1	their government and their great senate choose
1	through the twelve tribes to rule by laws ordained 
1	god from the mount of sinai whose gray top
1	shall tremble he descending will himself
1	in thunder lightning and loud trumpets sound 
1	ordain them laws part such as appertain
1	to civil justice part religious rites
1	of sacrifice informing them by types
1	and shadows of that destined seed to bruise
1	the serpent by what means he shall achieve
1	mankind s deliverance but the voice of god
1	to mortal ear is dreadful they beseech
1	that moses might report to them his will 
1	and terrour cease he grants what they besought 
1	instructed that to god is no access
1	without mediator whose high office now
1	moses in figure bears to introduce
1	one greater of whose day he shall foretel 
1	and all the prophets in their age the times
1	of great messiah shall sing thus laws and rites
1	established such delight hath god in men
1	obedient to his will that he vouchsafes
1	among them to set up his tabernacle 
1	the holy one with mortal men to dwell 
1	by his prescript a sanctuary is framed
1	of cedar overlaid with gold therein
1	an ark and in the ark his testimony 
1	the records of his covenant over these
1	a mercy seat of gold between the wings
1	of two bright cherubim before him burn
1	seven lamps as in a zodiack representing
1	the heavenly fires over the tent a cloud
1	shall rest by day a fiery gleam by night 
1	save when they journey and at length they come 
1	conducted by his angel to the land
1	promised to abraham and his seed the rest
1	were long to tell how many battles fought
1	how many kings destroyed and kingdoms won 
1	or how the sun shall in mid heaven stand still
1	a day entire and night s due course adjourn 
1	man s voice commanding sun in gibeon stand 
1	and thou moon in the vale of aialon 
1	till israel overcome so call the third
1	from abraham son of isaac and from him
1	his whole descent who thus shall canaan win 
1	here adam interposed o sent from heaven 
1	enlightener of my darkness gracious things
1	thou hast revealed those chiefly which concern
1	just abraham and his seed now first i find
1	mine eyes true opening and my heart much eased 
1	erewhile perplexed with thoughts what would become
1	of me and all mankind but now i see
1	his day in whom all nations shall be blest 
1	favour unmerited by me who sought
1	forbidden knowledge by forbidden means 
1	this yet i apprehend not why to those
1	among whom god will deign to dwell on earth
1	so many and so various laws are given 
1	so many laws argue so many sins
1	among them how can god with such reside 
1	to whom thus michael doubt not but that sin
1	will reign among them as of thee begot 
1	and therefore was law given them to evince
1	their natural pravity by stirring up
1	sin against law to fight that when they see
1	law can discover sin but not remove 
1	save by those shadowy expiations weak 
1	the blood of bulls and goats they may conclude
1	some blood more precious must be paid for man 
1	just for unjust that in such righteousness
1	to them by faith imputed they may find
1	justification towards god and peace
1	of conscience which the law by ceremonies
1	cannot appease nor man the mortal part
1	perform and not performing cannot live 
1	so law appears imperfect and but given
1	with purpose to resign them in full time 
1	up to a better covenant disciplined
1	from shadowy types to truth from flesh to spirit 
1	from imposition of strict laws to free
1	acceptance of large grace from servile fear
1	to filial works of law to works of faith 
1	and therefore shall not moses though of god
1	highly beloved being but the minister
1	of law his people into canaan lead 
1	but joshua whom the gentiles jesus call 
1	his name and office bearing who shall quell
1	the adversary serpent and bring back
1	through the world s wilderness long wandered man
1	safe to eternal paradise of rest 
1	mean while they in their earthly canaan placed 
1	long time shall dwell and prosper but when sins
1	national interrupt their publick peace 
1	provoking god to raise them enemies 
1	from whom as oft he saves them penitent
1	by judges first then under kings of whom
1	the second both for piety renowned
1	and puissant deeds a promise shall receive
1	irrevocable that his regal throne
1	for ever shall endure the like shall sing
1	all prophecy that of the royal stock
1	of david so i name this king shall rise
1	a son the woman s seed to thee foretold 
1	foretold to abraham as in whom shall trust
1	all nations and to kings foretold of kings
1	the last for of his reign shall be no end 
1	but first a long succession must ensue 
1	and his next son for wealth and wisdom famed 
1	the clouded ark of god till then in tents
1	wandering shall in a glorious temple enshrine 
1	such follow him as shall be registered
1	part good part bad of bad the longer scroll 
1	whose foul idolatries and other faults
1	heaped to the popular sum will so incense
1	god as to leave them and expose their land 
1	their city his temple and his holy ark 
1	with all his sacred things a scorn and prey
1	to that proud city whose high walls thou sawest
1	left in confusion babylon thence called 
1	there in captivity he lets them dwell
1	the space of seventy years then brings them back 
1	remembering mercy and his covenant sworn
1	to david stablished as the days of heaven 
1	returned from babylon by leave of kings
1	their lords whom god disposed the house of god
1	they first re edify and for a while
1	in mean estate live moderate till grown
1	in wealth and multitude factious they grow 
1	but first among the priests dissention springs 
1	men who attend the altar and should most
1	endeavour peace their strife pollution brings
1	upon the temple itself at last they seise
1	the scepter and regard not david s sons 
1	then lose it to a stranger that the true
1	anointed king messiah might be born
1	barred of his right yet at his birth a star 
1	unseen before in heaven proclaims him come 
1	and guides the eastern sages who inquire
1	his place to offer incense myrrh and gold 
1	his place of birth a solemn angel tells
1	to simple shepherds keeping watch by night 
1	they gladly thither haste and by a quire
1	of squadroned angels hear his carol sung 
1	a virgin is his mother but his sire
1	the power of the most high he shall ascend
1	the throne hereditary and bound his reign
1	with earth s wide bounds his glory with the heavens 
1	he ceased discerning adam with such joy
1	surcharged as had like grief been dewed in tears 
1	without the vent of words which these he breathed 
1	o prophet of glad tidings finisher
1	of utmost hope now clear i understand
1	what oft my steadiest thoughts have searched in vain 
1	why our great expectation should be called
1	the seed of woman virgin mother hail 
1	high in the love of heaven yet from my loins
1	thou shalt proceed and from thy womb the son
1	of god most high so god with man unites 
1	needs must the serpent now his capital bruise
1	expect with mortal pain say where and when
1	their fight what stroke shall bruise the victor s heel 
1	to whom thus michael dream not of their fight 
1	as of a duel or the local wounds
1	of head or heel not therefore joins the son
1	manhood to godhead with more strength to foil
1	thy enemy nor so is overcome
1	satan whose fall from heaven a deadlier bruise 
1	disabled not to give thee thy death s wound 
1	which he who comes thy saviour shall recure 
1	not by destroying satan but his works
1	in thee and in thy seed nor can this be 
1	but by fulfilling that which thou didst want 
1	obedience to the law of god imposed
1	on penalty of death and suffering death 
1	the penalty to thy transgression due 
1	and due to theirs which out of thine will grow 
1	so only can high justice rest appaid 
1	the law of god exact he shall fulfil
1	both by obedience and by love though love
1	alone fulfil the law thy punishment
1	he shall endure by coming in the flesh
1	to a reproachful life and cursed death 
1	proclaiming life to all who shall believe
1	in his redemption and that his obedience 
1	imputed becomes theirs by faith his merits
1	to save them not their own though legal works 
1	for this he shall live hated be blasphemed 
1	seised on by force judged and to death condemned
1	a shameful and accursed nailed to the cross
1	by his own nation slain for bringing life 
1	but to the cross he nails thy enemies 
1	the law that is against thee and the sins
1	of all mankind with him there crucified 
1	never to hurt them more who rightly trust
1	in this his satisfaction so he dies 
1	but soon revives death over him no power
1	shall long usurp ere the third dawning light
1	return the stars of morn shall see him rise
1	out of his grave fresh as the dawning light 
1	thy ransom paid which man from death redeems 
1	his death for man as many as offered life
1	neglect not and the benefit embrace
1	by faith not void of works this god like act
1	annuls thy doom the death thou shouldest have died 
1	in sin for ever lost from life this act
1	shall bruise the head of satan crush his strength 
1	defeating sin and death his two main arms 
1	and fix far deeper in his head their stings
1	than temporal death shall bruise the victor s heel 
1	or theirs whom he redeems a death like sleep 
1	a gentle wafting to immortal life 
1	nor after resurrection shall he stay
1	longer on earth than certain times to appear
1	to his disciples men who in his life
1	still followed him to them shall leave in charge
1	to teach all nations what of him they learned
1	and his salvation them who shall believe
1	baptizing in the profluent stream the sign
1	of washing them from guilt of sin to life
1	pure and in mind prepared if so befall 
1	for death like that which the redeemer died 
1	all nations they shall teach for from that day 
1	not only to the sons of abraham s loins
1	salvation shall be preached but to the sons
1	of abraham s faith wherever through the world 
1	so in his seed all nations shall be blest 
1	then to the heaven of heavens he shall ascend
1	with victory triumphing through the air
1	over his foes and thine there shall surprise
1	the serpent prince of air and drag in chains
1	through all his realm and there confounded leave 
1	then enter into glory and resume
1	his seat at god s right hand exalted high
1	above all names in heaven and thence shall come 
1	when this world s dissolution shall be ripe 
1	with glory and power to judge both quick and dead 
1	to judge the unfaithful dead but to reward
1	his faithful and receive them into bliss 
1	whether in heaven or earth for then the earth
1	shall all be paradise far happier place
1	than this of eden and far happier days 
1	so spake the arch angel michael then paused 
1	as at the world s great period and our sire 
1	replete with joy and wonder thus replied 
1	o goodness infinite goodness immense 
1	that all this good of evil shall produce 
1	and evil turn to good more wonderful
1	than that which by creation first brought forth
1	light out of darkness full of doubt i stand 
1	whether i should repent me now of sin
1	by me done and occasioned or rejoice
1	much more that much more good thereof shall spring 
1	to god more glory more good will to men
1	from god and over wrath grace shall abound 
1	but say if our deliverer up to heaven
1	must re ascend what will betide the few
1	his faithful left among the unfaithful herd 
1	the enemies of truth who then shall guide
1	his people who defend will they not deal
1	worse with his followers than with him they dealt 
1	be sure they will said the angel but from heaven
1	he to his own a comforter will send 
1	the promise of the father who shall dwell
1	his spirit within them and the law of faith 
1	working through love upon their hearts shall write 
1	to guide them in all truth and also arm
1	with spiritual armour able to resist
1	satan s assaults and quench his fiery darts 
1	what man can do against them not afraid 
1	though to the death against such cruelties
1	with inward consolations recompensed 
1	and oft supported so as shall amaze
1	their proudest persecutors for the spirit 
1	poured first on his apostles whom he sends
1	to evangelize the nations then on all
1	baptized shall them with wonderous gifts endue
1	to speak all tongues and do all miracles 
1	as did their lord before them thus they win
1	great numbers of each nation to receive
1	with joy the tidings brought from heaven at length
1	their ministry performed and race well run 
1	their doctrine and their story written left 
1	they die but in their room as they forewarn 
1	wolves shall succeed for teachers grievous wolves 
1	who all the sacred mysteries of heaven
1	to their own vile advantages shall turn
1	of lucre and ambition and the truth
1	with superstitions and traditions taint 
1	left only in those written records pure 
1	though not but by the spirit understood 
1	then shall they seek to avail themselves of names 
1	places and titles and with these to join
1	secular power though feigning still to act
1	by spiritual to themselves appropriating
1	the spirit of god promised alike and given
1	to all believers and from that pretence 
1	spiritual laws by carnal power shall force
1	on every conscience laws which none shall find
1	left them inrolled or what the spirit within
1	shall on the heart engrave what will they then
1	but force the spirit of grace itself and bind
1	his consort liberty what but unbuild
1	his living temples built by faith to stand 
1	their own faith not another s for on earth 
1	who against faith and conscience can be heard
1	infallible yet many will presume 
1	whence heavy persecution shall arise
1	on all who in the worship persevere
1	of spirit and truth the rest far greater part 
1	will deem in outward rites and specious forms
1	religion satisfied truth shall retire
1	bestuck with slanderous darts and works of faith
1	rarely be found so shall the world go on 
1	to good malignant to bad men benign 
1	under her own weight groaning till the day
1	appear of respiration to the just 
1	and vengeance to the wicked at return
1	of him so lately promised to thy aid 
1	the woman s seed obscurely then foretold 
1	now ampler known thy saviour and thy lord 
1	last in the clouds from heaven to be revealed
1	in glory of the father to dissolve
1	satan with his perverted world then raise
1	from the conflagrant mass purged and refined 
1	new heavens new earth ages of endless date 
1	founded in righteousness and peace and love 
1	to bring forth fruits joy and eternal bliss 
1	he ended and thus adam last replied 
1	how soon hath thy prediction seer blest 
1	measured this transient world the race of time 
1	till time stand fixed beyond is all abyss 
1	eternity whose end no eye can reach 
1	greatly instructed i shall hence depart 
1	greatly in peace of thought and have my fill
1	of knowledge what this vessel can contain 
1	beyond which was my folly to aspire 
1	henceforth i learn that to obey is best 
1	and love with fear the only god to walk
1	as in his presence ever to observe
1	his providence and on him sole depend 
1	merciful over all his works with good
1	still overcoming evil and by small
1	accomplishing great things by things deemed weak
1	subverting worldly strong and worldly wise
1	by simply meek that suffering for truth s sake
1	is fortitude to highest victory 
1	and to the faithful death the gate of life 
1	taught this by his example whom i now
1	acknowledge my redeemer ever blest 
1	to whom thus also the angel last replied 
1	this having learned thou hast attained the sum
1	of wisdom hope no higher though all the stars
1	thou knewest by name and all the ethereal powers 
1	all secrets of the deep all nature s works 
1	or works of god in heaven air earth or sea 
1	and all the riches of this world enjoyedst 
1	and all the rule one empire only add
1	deeds to thy knowledge answerable add faith 
1	add virtue patience temperance add love 
1	by name to come called charity the soul
1	of all the rest then wilt thou not be loth
1	to leave this paradise but shalt possess
1	a paradise within thee happier far 
1	let us descend now therefore from this top
1	of speculation for the hour precise
1	exacts our parting hence and see the guards 
1	by me encamped on yonder hill expect
1	their motion at whose front a flaming sword 
1	in signal of remove waves fiercely round 
1	we may no longer stay go waken eve 
1	her also i with gentle dreams have calmed
1	portending good and all her spirits composed
1	to meek submission thou at season fit 
1	let her with thee partake what thou hast heard 
1	chiefly what may concern her faith to know 
1	the great deliverance by her seed to come
1	 for by the woman s seed on all mankind 
1	that ye may live which will be many days 
1	both in one faith unanimous though sad 
1	with cause for evils past yet much more cheered
1	with meditation on the happy end 
1	he ended and they both descend the hill 
1	descended adam to the bower where eve
1	lay sleeping ran before but found her waked 
1	and thus with words not sad she him received 
1	whence thou returnest and whither wentest i know 
1	for god is also in sleep and dreams advise 
1	which he hath sent propitious some great good
1	presaging since with sorrow and heart s distress
1	wearied i fell asleep but now lead on 
1	in me is no delay with thee to go 
1	is to stay here without thee here to stay 
1	is to go hence unwilling thou to me
1	art all things under heaven all places thou 
1	who for my wilful crime art banished hence 
1	this further consolation yet secure
1	i carry hence though all by me is lost 
1	such favour i unworthy am vouchsafed 
1	by me the promised seed shall all restore 
1	so spake our mother eve and adam heard
1	well pleased but answered not for now too nigh
1	the arch angel stood and from the other hill
1	to their fixed station all in bright array
1	the cherubim descended on the ground
1	gliding meteorous as evening mist
1	risen from a river o er the marish glides 
1	and gathers ground fast at the labourer s heel
1	homeward returning high in front advanced 
1	the brandished sword of god before them blazed 
1	fierce as a comet which with torrid heat 
1	and vapour as the libyan air adust 
1	began to parch that temperate clime whereat
1	in either hand the hastening angel caught
1	our lingering parents and to the eastern gate
1	led them direct and down the cliff as fast
1	to the subjected plain then disappeared 
1	they looking back all the eastern side beheld
1	of paradise so late their happy seat 
1	waved over by that flaming brand the gate
1	with dreadful faces thronged and fiery arms 
1	some natural tears they dropt but wiped them soon 
1	the world was all before them where to choose
1	their place of rest and providence their guide 
1	they hand in hand with wandering steps and slow 
1	through eden took their solitary way 
1	 of cerberus and blackest midnight born
1	in stygian cave forlorn
1	unholy 
1	find out some uncouth cell 
1	 where brooding darkness spreads his jealous wings 
1	and the night raven sings 
1	as ragged as thy locks 
1	but come thou goddess fair and free 
1	in heaven yclept euphrosyne 
1	and by men heart easing mirth 
1	whom lovely venus at a birth 
1	with two sister graces more 
1	to ivy crowned bacchus bore 
1	hence loathed melancholy 
1	or whether as some sager sing 
1	the frolic wind that breathes the spring 
1	zephyr with aurora playing 
1	as he met her once a maying 
1	there on beds of violets blue 
1	and fresh blown roses washed in dew 
1	filled her with thee a daughter fair 
1	so buxom blithe and debonair 
1	haste thee nymph and bring with thee
1	jest and youthful jollity 
1	quips and cranks and wanton wiles 
1	nods and becks and wreathed smiles
1	such as hang on hebe s cheek 
1	and love to live in dimple sleek 
1	sport that wrinkled care derides 
1	and laughter holding both his sides 
1	come and trip it as you go 
1	on the light fantastic toe 
1	and in thy right hand lead with thee
1	the mountain nymph sweet liberty 
1	and if i give thee honour due 
1	mirth admit me of thy crew 
1	to live with her and live with thee 
1	in unreproved pleasures free 
1	to hear the lark begin his flight 
1	and singing startle the dull night 
1	from his watch tower in the skies 
1	till the dappled dawn doth rise 
1	then to come in spite of sorrow 
1	and at my window bid good morrow 
1	through the sweet briar or the vine 
1	or the twisted eglantine 
1	while the cock with lively din 
1	scatters the rear of darkness thin 
1	and to the stack or the barn door 
1	stoutly struts his dames before 
1	oft listening how the hounds and horn
1	cheerly rouse the slumbering morn 
1	from the side of some hoar hill 
1	through the high wood echoing shrill 
1	sometime walking not unseen 
1	by hedgerow elms on hillocks green 
1	right against the eastern gate
1	where the great sun begins his state 
1	robed in flames and amber light 
1	the clouds in thousand liveries dight 
1	while the ploughman near at hand 
1	whistles o er the furrowed land 
1	and the milkmaid singeth blithe 
1	and the mower whets his scythe 
1	and every shepherd tells his tale
1	under the hawthorn in the dale 
1	straight mine eye hath caught new pleasures 
1	whilst the landskip round it measures 
1	russet lawns and fallows grey 
1	where the nibbling flocks do stray 
1	mountains on whose barren breast
1	the labouring clouds do often rest 
1	meadows trim with daisies pied 
1	shallow brooks and rivers wide 
1	towers and battlements it sees
1	bosomed high in tufted trees 
1	where perhaps some beauty lies 
1	the cynosure of neighbouring eyes 
1	hard by a cottage chimney smokes
1	from betwixt two aged oaks 
1	are at their savoury dinner set
1	of herbs and other country messes 
1	which the neat handed phyllis dresses 
1	and then in haste her bower she leaves 
1	with thestylis to bind the sheaves 
1	or if the earlier season lead 
1	to the tanned haycock in the mead 
1	sometimes with secure delight 
1	the upland hamlets will invite 
1	when the merry bells ring round 
1	and the jocund rebecks sound
1	to many a youth and many a maid
1	dancing in the chequered shade 
1	and young and old come forth to play
1	on a sunshine holiday 
1	till the livelong daylight fail 
1	then to the spicy nut brown ale 
1	with stories told of many a feat 
1	how faery mab the junkets eat 
1	she was pinched and pulled she said 
1	and he by friar s lantern led 
1	tells how the drudging goblin sweat
1	to earn his cream bowl duly set 
1	when in one night ere glimpse of morn 
1	his shadowy flail hath threshed the corn
1	that ten day labourers could not end 
1	then lies him down the lubber fiend 
1	and stretched out all the chimney s length 
1	basks at the fire his hairy strength 
1	and crop full out of doors he flings 
1	ere the first cock his matin rings 
1	thus done the tales to bed they creep 
1	by whispering winds soon lulled asleep 
1	towered cities please us then 
1	and the busy hum of men 
1	where throngs of knights and barons bold 
1	in weeds of peace high triumphs hold
1	with store of ladies whose bright eyes
1	rain influence and judge the prize
1	of wit or arms while both contend
1	to win her grace whom all commend 
1	there let hymen oft appear
1	in saffron robe with taper clear 
1	and pomp and feast and revelry 
