1	 sec bro what hidden strength 
1	unless the strength of heaven if you mean that 
1	 eld bro i mean that too but yet a hidden strength 
1	which if heaven gave it may be termed her own 
1	 tis chastity my brother chastity 
1	she that has that is clad in complete steel 
1	and like a quivered nymph with arrows keen 
1	may trace huge forests and unharbored heaths 
1	infamous hills and sandy perilous wilds 
1	where through the sacred rays of chastity 
1	no savage fierce bandite or mountaineer 
1	will dare to soil her virgin purity 
1	yea there where very desolation dwells 
1	by grots and caverns shagged with horrid shades 
1	she may pass on with unblenched majesty 
1	be it not done in pride or in presumption 
1	some say no evil thing that walks by night 
1	in fog or fire by lake or moorish fen 
1	blue meagre hag or stubborn unlaid ghost 
1	that breaks his magic chains at curfew time 
1	no goblin or swart faery of the mine 
1	hath hurtful power o er true virginity 
1	do ye believe me yet or shall i call
1	antiquity from the old schools of greece
1	to testify the arms of chastity 
1	hence had the huntress dian her dread bow 
1	fair silver shafted queen forever chaste 
1	wherewith she tamed the brinded lioness
1	and spotted mountain pard but set at nought
1	the frivolous bolt of cupid gods and men
1	feared her stern frown and she was queen o the woods 
1	what was that snaky headed gorgon shield
1	that wise minerva wore unconquered virgin 
1	wherewith she freezed her foes to congealed stone 
1	but rigid looks of chaste austerity 
1	and noble grace that dashed brute violence
1	with sudden adoration and blank awe 
1	so dear to heaven is saintly chastity
1	that when a soul is found sincerely so 
1	a thousand liveried angels lackey her 
1	driving far off each thing of sin and guilt 
1	and in clear dream and solemn vision
1	tell her of things that no gross ear can hear 
1	till oft converse with heavenly habitants
1	begin to cast a beam on the outward shape 
1	the unpolluted temple of the mind 
1	and turns it by degrees to the soul s essence 
1	till all be made immortal but when lust 
1	by unchaste looks loose gestures and foul talk 
1	but most by lewd and lavish act of sin 
1	lets in defilement to the inward parts 
1	the soul grows clotted by contagion 
1	imbodies and imbrutes till she quite lose
1	the divine property of her first being 
1	such are those thick and gloomy shadows damp
1	oft seen in charnel vaults and sepulchres 
1	lingering and sitting by a new made grave 
1	as loth to leave the body that it loved 
1	and linked itself by carnal sensualty
1	to a degenerate and degraded state 
1	 sec bro how charming is divine philosophy 
1	not harsh and crabbed as dull fools suppose 
1	but musical as is apollo s lute 
1	and a perpetual feast of nectared sweets 
1	where no crude surfeit reigns 
