1	to luxurie and riot feast and dance 
1	marrying or prostituting as befell 
1	rape or adulterie where passing faire
1	allurd them thence from cups to civil broiles 
1	at length a reverend sire among them came 
1	and of thir doings great dislike declar d 
1	and testifi d against thir wayes hee oft
1	frequented thir assemblies whereso met 
1	triumphs or festivals and to them preachd
1	in prison under judgements imminent 
1	but all in vain which when he saw he ceas d
1	contending and remov d his tents farr off 
1	then from the mountain hewing timber tall 
1	began to build a vessel of huge bulk 
1	measur d by cubit length breadth and highth 
1	smeard round with pitch and in the side a dore
1	contriv d and of provisions laid in large
1	for man and beast when loe a wonder strange 
1	of everie beast and bird and insect small
1	came seavens and pairs and enterd in as taught
1	thir order last the sire and his three sons
1	with thir four wives and god made fast the dore 
1	meanwhile the southwind rose with black wings
1	wide hovering all the clouds together drove
1	from under heav n the hills to their supplie
1	vapour and exhalation dusk and moist 
1	sent up amain and now the thick nd skie
1	like a dark ceeling stood down rush d the rain
1	impetuous and continu d till the earth
1	no more was seen the floating vessel swum
1	uplifted and secure with beaked prow
1	rode tilting o re the waves all dwellings else
1	flood overwhelmd and them with all thir pomp
1	deep under water rould sea cover d sea 
1	sea without shoar and in thir palaces
1	where luxurie late reign d sea monsters whelp d
1	and stabl d of mankind so numerous late 
1	all left in one small bottom swum imbark t 
1	how didst thou grieve then adam to behold
1	the end of all thy ofspring end so sad 
1	depopulation thee another floud 
1	of tears and sorrow a floud thee also drown d 
1	and sunk thee as thy sons till gently reard
1	by th angel on thy feet thou stoodst at last 
1	though comfortless as when a father mourns
1	his childern all in view destroyd at once 
1	and scarce to th angel utterdst thus thy plaint 
1	o visions ill foreseen better had i
1	liv d ignorant of future so had borne
1	my part of evil onely each dayes lot
1	anough to bear those now that were dispenst
1	the burd n of many ages on me light
1	at once by my foreknowledge gaining birth
1	abortive to torment me ere thir being 
1	with thought that they must be let no man seek
1	henceforth to be foretold what shall befall
1	him or his childern evil he may be sure 
1	which neither his foreknowing can prevent 
1	and hee the future evil shall no less
1	in apprehension then in substance feel
1	grievous to bear but that care now is past 
1	man is not whom to warne those few escap t
1	famin and anguish will at last consume
1	wandring that watrie desert i had hope
1	when violence was ceas t and warr on earth 
1	all would have then gon well peace would have crownd
1	with length of happy days the race of man 
1	but i was farr deceav d for now i see
1	peace to corrupt no less then warr to waste 
1	how comes it thus unfould celestial guide 
1	and whether here the race of man will end 
1	to whom thus michael those whom last thou sawst
1	in triumph and luxurious wealth are they
1	first seen in acts of prowess eminent
1	and great exploits but of true vertu void 
1	who having spilt much blood and don much waste
1	subduing nations and achievd thereby
1	fame in the world high titles and rich prey 
1	shall change thir course to pleasure ease and sloth 
1	surfet and lust till wantonness and pride
1	raise out of friendship hostil deeds in peace 
1	the conquerd also and enslav d by warr
1	shall with thir freedom lost all vertu loose
1	and feare of god from whom thir pietie feign d
1	in sharp contest of battel found no aide
1	against invaders therefore coold in zeale
1	thenceforth shall practice how to live secure 
1	worldlie or dissolute on what thir lords
1	shall leave them to enjoy for th earth shall bear
1	more then anough that temperance may be tri d 
1	so all shall turn degenerate all deprav d 
1	justice and temperance truth and faith forgot 
1	one man except the onely son of light
1	in a dark age against example good 
1	against allurement custom and a world
1	offended fearless of reproach and scorn 
1	or violence hee of thir wicked wayes
1	shall them admonish and before them set
1	the paths of righteousness how much more safe 
1	and full of peace denouncing wrauth to come
1	on thir impenitence and shall returne
1	of them derided but of god observd
1	the one just man alive by his command
1	shall build a wondrous ark as thou beheldst 
1	to save himself and houshold from amidst
1	a world devote to universal rack 
1	no sooner hee with them of man and beast
1	select for life shall in the ark be lodg d 
1	and shelterd round but all the cataracts
1	of heav n set open on the earth shall powre
1	raine day and night all fountaines of the deep
1	broke up shall heave the ocean to usurp
1	beyond all bounds till inundation rise
1	above the highest hills then shall this mount
1	of paradise by might of waves be moovd
1	out of his place pushd by the horned floud 
1	with all his verdure spoil d and trees adrift
1	down the great river to the op ning gulf 
1	and there take root an iland salt and bare 
1	the haunt of seales and orcs and sea mews clang 
1	to teach thee that god attributes to place
1	no sanctitie if none be thither brought
1	by men who there frequent or therein dwell 
1	and now what further shall ensue behold 
1	he lookd and saw the ark hull on the floud 
1	which now abated for the clouds were fled 
1	drivn by a keen north winde that blowing drie
1	wrinkl d the face of deluge as decai d 
1	and the cleer sun on his wide watrie glass
1	gaz d hot and of the fresh wave largely drew 
1	as after thirst which made thir flowing shrink
1	from standing lake to tripping ebbe that stole
1	with soft foot towards the deep who now had stopt
1	his sluces as the heav n his windows shut 
1	the ark no more now flotes but seems on ground
1	fast on the top of som high mountain fixt 
1	and now the tops of hills as rocks appeer 
1	with clamor thence the rapid currents drive
1	towards the retreating sea thir furious tyde 
1	forthwith from out the arke a raven flies 
1	and after him the surer messenger 
1	a dove sent forth once and agen to spie
1	green tree or ground whereon his foot may light 
1	the second time returning in his bill
1	an olive leafe he brings pacific signe 
1	anon drie ground appeers and from his arke
1	the ancient sire descends with all his train 
1	then with uplifted hands and eyes devout 
1	grateful to heav n over his head beholds
1	a dewie cloud and in the cloud a bow
1	conspicuous with three lifted colours gay 
1	betok ning peace from god and cov nant new 
1	whereat the heart of adam erst so sad
1	greatly rejoyc d and thus his joy broke forth 
1	o thou that future things canst represent
1	as present heav nly instructer i revive
1	at this last sight assur d that man shall live
1	with all the creatures and thir seed preserve 
1	farr less i now lament for one whole world
1	of wicked sons destroyd then i rejoyce
1	for one man found so perfet and so just 
1	that god voutsafes to raise another world
1	from him and all his anger to forget 
1	but say what mean those colourd streaks in heavn 
1	distended as the brow of god appeas d 
1	or serve they as a flourie verge to binde
1	the fluid skirts of that same watrie cloud 
1	least it again dissolve and showr the earth 
1	to whom th archangel dextrously thou aim st 
1	so willingly doth god remit his ire 
1	though late repenting him of man deprav d 
1	griev d at his heart when looking down he saw
1	the whole earth fill d with violence and all flesh
1	corrupting each thir way yet those remoov d 
